<HEAD>Final Action on Tax Bill Delayed as Senate Deals With Unrelated
Amendments</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `The bill's' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Manassas battlefield vote; Should stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Friday beat back a series of unrelated amendments to a catchall tax bill, including one designed to benefit 2 million owners of home satellite dishes. But consideration of such proposals delayed until next week final action on the tax bill, which includes a `` bill of rights'' for taxpayers involved in disputes with the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, and special relief worth $ 2.7 billion over three years for various groups, including farmers, artists and first-time homebuyers. By nightfall, an angry majority leader, Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, counted more than 100 proposed amendments still awaiting action and coaxed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> into cutting off any `` This list is crazy, nuts and getting crazier all the time,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` We ought to settle down and get our senses.'' Within two hours, <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> announced senators had agreed to drop all but 29. Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> sided with <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, noting amendments dealing with everything but taxes, including sanctions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, aid to the <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> rebels and a move to halt commercial development of the historic <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> battlefield in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. `` This is the typical tax bill,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` Everybody cleans out their desks and their trash cans and says ` we'll put it on the tax bill.' We've reached the point that if somebody does n't take the bull by the horns, we'll never finish.'' On the <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> battlefield issue, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 50-25 to approve an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Bumpers </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., requiring the federal government to seize 540 acres of land to prevent further development on the site about 30 miles west of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> The House has approved the same provision, but the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary has said he will recommend that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> veto it. In siding with <PERSON> Bumpers </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> defeated a plan by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., to authorize the taking of only 80 acres and allow development of housing on adjacent areas The tax bill's main purpose is to correct errors in the big tax overhaul enacted in 1986. But since this is the only tax bill with a chance of becoming law this year, senators view it as the last opportunity to have their pet amendments considered. But there is no assurance it will become law. The version approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is considerably different and there is some doubt that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> can negotiate a compromise before quitting next week. In a long day of debate over the bill, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> considered and rejected amendments calling for: _ An end to what Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Tenn., called discrimination against owners of home satellite dishes by television His amendment was aimed at helping the 2 million dish owners, most of them living in rural areas, whose television and satellite dish have become prime sources of contact with the outside world. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s amendment would have required that programs provided to cable systems be made available to dish owners, and ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to extend network programming into isolated areas that can not receive broadcast signals. Opponents, led by Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, said the amendment was unnecessary, that `` there are no unfair trade practices in pricing and distribution of satellite programming.'' Managers of the bill said <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s amendment had no chances of becoming law as part of the tax legislation. _ An 18-month study of whether government workers should get equal pay for jobs of comparable worth Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, R-Wash., proposed the study and was opposed vigorously by conservatives, who said it would lead to new federal requirements for what any worker could be paid <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> called the dissent `` blind opposition to knowledge.'' _ A symbolic endorsement of the right of the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> to finance abortions for poor women _ Raising from $ 17 a month to $ 38 the maximum tax-free mass-transit benefits that an employer could furnish workers Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, offered the amendment in the name of fairness, saying the government already provides a much higher subsidy for corporate executives to park their limousines. He would have paid for the change by doubling, to a maximum of $ 7,700, the tax imposed on gas-guzzling cars _ most of them luxury imports.
