<SECOND>PM-Medical Waste,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To Track Medical Waste From Start to Finish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is moving to slap controls on medical waste, from the vials of AIDS-infected blood washing up on <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> beaches to the used hypodermic needles picked out of trash bins by children in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The vehicle to attack the growing problem of carelessly discarded medical waste is a bill that would require a so-far reluctant <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to set up a system to track the waste from creation to disposal. The legislation, given impetus by this summer's publicized cases of infectious materials littering ocean and Great Lakes shorelines, was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday by a 390-28 margin. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has approved a more limited control blueprint. Lawmakers in both chambers say they see no difficulty working out a joint product that can be sent to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns next week. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, says action is needed because `` the illegal disposal of medical waste is spreading like an epidemic across the country. This waste is not just repulsive, it can literally kill people. `` According to recent federal studies, as many as 18,000 people each year may contract hepatitis B from accidental contact with medical waste,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. `` Hundreds of those infected will ultimately die from the infection.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan would cover waste produced by hospitals, clinics and labs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> states of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. The program, however, could become national in scope because any other state could decide to have its waste covered by the plan and gain authority to act against incoming waste not meeting the tracking system's requirements. `` This is a national problem,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore. `` The medical waste system in this country is broken It is overloaded, and in effect it is starting to regurgitate what it can not keep down.'' Expected to form the basis for the final bill, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan would apply to 10 types of medical waste, including blood, hypodermic needles, scalpels and surgical and laboratory waste that has been in contact with infectious agents. The enumerated items would have to be segregated from other medical waste. The tracking system would have to contain assurances that a generator knows the waste reached a disposal facility. The legislation does not, however, set any standards for actual disposal, such as burning or using a hazardous waste landfill. Supporters said there was no time this year to work out these details. They add, however, that it already is illegal to dump such waste into waterways. Violators of the tracking requirements could be slapped with a civil fine of up to $ 25,000 for each day of violation and a maximum criminal penalty of two years in prison and a fine of up to $ 50,000 per day of violation. <PERSON> Luken </PERSON> said the medical waste problem goes beyond the beach foulings that closed stretches of oceanfront in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> the past two summers. `` Last year, careless doctors in <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> -RRB- and <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> put contaminated needles and vials of infected blood into dumpsters,'' he said. `` Kids found the needles and blood vials and played ` doctor' with them _ splattering blood on each other and giving each other injections that could have proved fatal.'' House members said they believe <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> already has the authority to act against medical trash under various hazardous waste control laws. In 1978, the agency announced plans to regulate medical waste, but six years later it said lacked evidence those wastes were causing enough harm to justify regulations. Instead, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> released a package of advice to hospitals on handling and disposal. Since then, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has formed a task force to rethink the issue. `` EPA has dragged its feet on this matter,'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. `` EPA told us that as of this summer, they had budgeted exactly one staff position to deal with the medical waste issue. That is why we need this legislation.''
