<FIRST>r w PM-Mother'sMilk Bjt   10-07 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mother's Milk, Bjt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reports New Means Of Fortifying Mother's Milk</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for PM-Farm Scene</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new recipe has been developed for fortifying mother's milk to help premature babies `` barely bigger than a man's hand'' survive and grow normally, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said `` The immune properties found in mother's milk are so much more important to preterm infants because they are subject to many more infections than full-term infants,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON>, physician in charge of the project at the Children's <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. But extremely premature babies, some of them weighing less than two pounds at birth, require more concentrated nutrients than mother's milk provides, he said. Most currently get a preemie formula based on cow's milk until they reach about three pounds and are growing well. After that, some may be switched to mother's milk mixed with a commercial fortifier. Concern about the practice of feeding the formulas to the tiny infants during their first month of life prompted <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON> and a former colleague, Dr. <PERSON> Cutberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, now at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, to look into ways of using breast milk from birth. Their research at the center, which is based at <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and is funded by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, included tests of commercial formulas and new recipe possibilities. The work was described in a report issued Thursday by the agency. <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON> said the new recipe includes mineral salts that are readily absorbed by the infants, and protein and energy from powdered skim mother's milk supplied by the center's own human milk bank. Although the recipe is being used for research purposes, <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON> said he doubts whether it will be feasible to produce a commercial fortifier made from human milk, noting that there are n't many human milk banks for this purpose But he said the findings from the recipe research should lead to better fortifiers so that very low-birth-weight infants can have the infection fighting factors present in breast milk when they most need it right after birth. The milk would still have to be taken from the mother with a breast pump, fortified with the forumla and fed to the baby through a tube. The initial concern has been to get enough protein and energy into the tiny babies, and `` we did n't pay much attention to minerals,'' <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON> said. Calcium and phosphorous were the main problem, a lack of which could `` compromise growth, impair healing of chronic lung disease and lead to bone malformations,'' <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON> said. The scientists came close to matching the `` in-the-womb retention levels'' of these minerals by adding calcium lactate and sodium or potassium phosphate to mother's milk. Infants averaging only 2.2 pounds at birth retained 86 percent of the calcium and 80 percent of the phosphorous they would have retained if still in their mother's uterus and are `` the best rates we have seen,'' <PERSON> Schanler </PERSON> said. According to <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, who now directs nutritional sciences at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION>, the government's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> requires formula companies to add a minimum amount of calcium without sufficient regard to its form. `` That's not enough for these tiny infants,'' <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said. `` You need to look at the form as well as the amount.'' For example, <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said, the calcium salt added to commercial formulas is tribasic calcium phosphate, which is not very soluble. `` It's like rock,'' he said. `` Most of it probably does n't get absorbed -LRB- into the infant's system -RRB- but comes out in the stool. Calcium lactate is much better utilized.'' Although the scientists recognize that human milk has less calcium and phosphorous than both regular and preemie formulas, they say the minerals are in a form more easily absorbed by the infants. Also human milk may have unknown factors that enhance infants' absorption and retention. Formula companies have not been able to duplicate these conditions in commercial preparations and compensate by increasing the concentration of minerals, the report said. Another former colleague, Dr. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, a physician now at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said the higher concentrations of minerals in commercial formulas may benefit the very low-birth-weight infants after they leave the hospital. After discharge, the mothers either chose to continue on unfortified breast milk or switch to regular infant formula. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, who tracked the infants for a year, found that the breast-fed babies had a lower bone mineral content than those who got commerical formulas. But they grew equally well on either, he said. Body weight, length and head measurements were the same for both groups. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> recommended that pediatricians regularly evaluate the mineral status of nursing preemies, but he added that `` the risks do not outweigh the benefits of breast feeding.''
