<HEAD>Congresswomen Push for Medicare Payments for Mammography
Screenings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two congresswomen say they will push for legislation next year to allow full Medicare coverage for elderly women seeking mammography screenings, the X-ray technique used to detect early signs of breast cancer. `` We need to promote preventive medicine, not just pay for care once an illness has set in,'' Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday. Mrs. <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON> said the Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act, enacted into law earlier this year, included a $ 50 reimbursement provision for the mammograms. `` A $ 50 mammogram is not readily available in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' the congresswoman said. `` The average cost for a mammogram ranges from $ 80 to $ 200.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON> said the only place a woman can receive a mammogram for $ 50 is mobile van clinics. `` Most women, especially older women, simply will not submit to being examined by a stranger in a van in the parking lot of a shopping mall,'' she said. `` Not only is a woman more likely to undergo the test when under the care of someone she knows and with whom she is comfortable, but doctors are more able to identify changes over time, and are able to provide the analysis, counseling and follow-up that are necessary to effectively care for patients,'' she said. A bill introduced by Mrs. <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON> would remove the $ 50 cap, making Medicare coverage for mammogram screenings the same as for mammograms for women already diagnosed with breast cancer. The Office of Technology Assessment has estimated that screening women over 65 could reduce the breast cancer mortality rate by 50 percent after five years, according to Mrs. <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON>. `` Breast cancer took the lives of 45,000 women in 1987, of which 28,000 were over age 65. Many of those lives could have been saved if mammograms were readily available and affordable to those women,'' she told a Capitol news conference. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> recommends that women over 40 undergo mammography screenings annually.
