 The Rev. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> plans a retirement village on his <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> that will offer senior citizens everything but a graveyard. `` No plans for a cemetery,'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> quipped Thursday as he unveiled blueprints for the $ 210 million <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Village </ORGANIZATION>, which he hopes will house some 3,000 residents on a site overlooking <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, the Christian school he founded. <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said he has already had numerous inquiries from people interested in paying `` entrance fees'' ranging from $ 59,000 for a ground-floor studio apartment to $ 176,000 for a three-bedroom penthouse. The residents also would pay an additional $ 850 to $ 1,600 per month as a service fee. When they die, or if they otherwise leave the apartments, at least half of the entrance fee will go to their estate. <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said residents will probably be the same sort of elderly Christians who watch his `` Old-Time Gospel Hour'' program and make donations to his ministry, although the development will be open to anyone over age 60 who can pay the entrance fee. The venture, which includes restaurants and stores, will be funded and built by <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <ORGANIZATION> Belleair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bluffs </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, a private developer. The project will need city approval, and <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> was careful Thursday to indicate he was not planning to stage a repeat of any of his past feuding with <LOCATION> Lynchburg </LOCATION> over taxes he refused to pay.
