<FIRST>r i PM-YugoslaviaQ&amp;A     10-07 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia Q&amp;A,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Problems Complicated By Government Structure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Yugoslavia, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s complex, cumbersome government structure and diversity of nationalities are major factors in its worsening ethnic and economic problems. Here is some background in question-and-answer form: Q: How does the government work? A: <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is a federation of six republics and two autonomous provinces that are administrative parts of the largest republic, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. Power rests in the League of Communists, or <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Each republic and province has its own party hierarchy for political leadership and its own government for administration. Each republic and autonomous province sends representatives to the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> leadership, headed by a 23-member Politburo, and the nine-man federal presidency. Leadership of those two bodies rotates annually. Only the premier of the federal government, which is primarily responsible for overseeing the economy and national defense, holds office for four years. The premier can be removed by a majority vote of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Q: Why is the system so complex? A: The 23 million Yugoslavs include about 30 nationalities. In an apparent attempt to prevent ethnic strife after his death, President <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> approved a 1974 constitution giving broad powers to each republic and province. He decreed that all decisions on major political questions must be approved by the leaderships of all republics and provinces, and national leadership posts would rotate annually to keep any republic from dominating. Q: What happened after <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>'s death in 1980? A: Unanimity is so hard to achieve that federal decision are weak compromises, and the largely state-run economy has deteriorated as a result. The foreign debt is $ 21 billion, unemployment 15 percent and the annual inflation rate 217 percent. More than 1,500 strikes were reported in 1987. Economic and political differences have grown between the rich northern region, which looks to the West, and the poorer, more backward south. Q: What is causing the current unrest? A: A mixture of ethnic strife, economic crisis and an ineffective political system. One fundamental element is the ethnic dispute in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, a backward autonomous province in south that was the heart of medieval <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s great empire. <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> now is dominated by predominantly Moslem ethnic <PERSON> Albanians </PERSON>, who have the highest birthrate in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and are 90 percent of the province's 2 million people. Minority Serbs, most of whom are <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, say they are being harassed and began holding rallies in July. Serbs in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> found a supporter in the Serbian Communist party leader, <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who is trying to impose more Serbian control on <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and the other autonomous province, <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s opponents accuse him of using the street protests to seek greater national power for himself and <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
