<FIRST>r i PM-DelaMadrid     10-07 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-De la Madrid,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Relations With US Difficult But Make Mexico More
Independent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a difficult neighbor, but living next to such a powerful country has made <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> more independent. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said that during his six-year term the two countries have improved understanding on the thorny issue of illegal drug trafficking. Industrialized countries in general, he said, have begun to understand that developing nations' foreign debt problems affect the entire world economy. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, 54, turns the government over to his successor, former Budget Secretary <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, on Dec. 1, after presiding over some of the country's most difficult years. Both men are from the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has not lost a major office since it was founded in 1929. `` Relations between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have always been very difficult, so difficult that we lost half our territory in the last century,'' de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said in the interview Wednesday. But the challenge of living next to such a wealthy and complicated country, he said, has made Mexicans more nationalistic. `` Perhaps that is one of the great advantages of being a neighbor of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>: our desire to continue being an independent and sovereign nation that rules its own destiny,'' he said. `` I believe the basis of the problems is a lack of knowledge of each other,'' de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said. Two-thirds of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s trade, tourism and investment are from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and there is a constant flow of citizens back and forth across the border. The result is continuous problems of immigration, trade, drug trafficking and foreign policy differences, particularly on <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> backs rebels fighting <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government and supports the <LOCATION> Salvadoran </LOCATION> government's war against leftist rebels there. It has failed to win the support it would like from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which opposes the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention and has been more sympathetic to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s government and the Salvadoran rebels. `` There are some in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> who think that because <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is an independent country with its own foreign policy that it is not a friend of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` I do not believe that is true. We are friends of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but in some things we do not think alike.'' Illegal narcotics trafficking through <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has been one of the biggest sources of conflict between the two countries during de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s term. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and other top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have recognized <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s efforts to fight drug trafficking, de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said. However, he added, `` there are lower-level officials who, to avoid responsibility, put the blame on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. It seems to me an infantile attitude.'' He said he believed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have recognized the importance of demand for illegal drugs in the problem of drug trafficking. `` That is a great advance, since you have to accept the reality that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the biggest consumer of drugs in the world and that constitutes an enormous motive to promote production or transportation from other parts of the world,'' he said. He said there were `` slight and tenuous signs'' of understanding that the developing countries' huge foreign debts have worldwide implications. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s $ 104 billion foreign debt is the second highest in the Third World, after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON> said both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential candidates, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, along with European leaders, have recognized that ways must be found to overcome the problem. `` What is needed now is for that recognition to be converted into political will and specific formulas,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> insists on joint responsibility of debtor and creditor for the debt,'' he said. `` It is not possible that, in the case of the Latin American countries, we resign ourselves to the economic stagnation of a growing population with so many needs.'' He said debtor nations must `` set our house in order internally'' while demanding `` a fair and realistic deal from creditors.'' De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> has maintained <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s commitment to keep up with debt service payments, establishing unpopular austerity measures. Subsidies were eliminated, prices went up and workers' salaries lost more than half their buying power. `` But my concern was to protect the majorities and to do that we had to defend the productive sectors and employment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
