<HEAD>Questions Linger on Quayle's Fitness for No. 2 Job, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> missed a once-in-a-campaign opportunity to bury doubts about his competence to serve as president if need be, several political analysts say. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s halting and at times unresponsive answers at the vice presidential debate to repeated questions about his readiness to lead the country left some Republicans shaking their heads. `` As a Republican, I sat there trying to pull words out of his mouth,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> consultant <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Edmonds </PERSON>. `` Frankly, I think there are a lot of family dogs that could have answered the question better.'' `` I think he was so afraid of striking out that he never swung the bat,'' <PERSON> Edmonds </PERSON> said. During Wednesday's debate in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> colleague <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> repeatedly cited his 12 years' service in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as his principal qualification for the vice presidency. When asked what he would do in the event of a presidential death, the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator said he would pray for himself and the country and then call a meeting of Cabinet members and top presidential advisers. He said little more, though pressed by questioners. Among those dissatisfied with the response was conservative direct-mail fund-raiser <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, who said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> did all right on all the questions but those concerning his qualification and fitness for the vice presidency. `` I'm sympathetic to the guy because he was too coached ... and told, ` Whatever you do, do n't do this and do n't do that,''' <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> said. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign chairman, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bake