<HEAD>Endangered Bird Spotted In Kansas City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dead quail have been placed at several downtown locations in an effort to attract and identify an endangered peregrine falcon that has been spotted flying among office buildings. `` We're not sure when it showed up,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Werner </PERSON>, an urban biologist for the <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` We had two last year, December through March.'' The falcon has an identification band on its leg, but conservationists will need a closer look to determine where it came from. One of the birds spotted last year was discovered to be from the Yukon; the other was hatched at a conservation site in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>. To attract the bird and determine its origin, the <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is putting dead quail on a ledge on the 18th floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> and in a nesting box atop another building, <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> said Conservationists think the bird may have come from a falcon release site in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, the nearest such site to <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Six falcons recently were released there, <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> said. If the new falcon was hatched in captivity, it should be attracted to the quail, the main meal at the release sites. Wild falcons generally do n't eat killed prey, feeding instead on live birds they snare as they swoop down at up to 200 mph from their perches, <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> said this is the migration season for the birds, which fly each year to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Workers downtown hope the birds will stick around awhile. `` It's really been t