<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed federal regulation to require regular drug testing of atomic plant workers is under attack on Capitol Hill for lacking similar standards to curb alcohol abuse. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission announced a proposed `` fitness for duty'' rule last month that would require reactor owners to conduct random drug tests, test employees based on cause, report drug use to the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> and mandate personnel sanctions. The proposal also would require utilities to submit their own alcohol programs providing `` reasonable assurance'' that plant operators are sober, but `` leaves to the discretion of each licensee the specific measures to be used,'' <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Thursday. `` It is as if the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> is saying that it is less concerned with someone being drunk in the control room than it is with someone being high on drugs,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> and Insular Affairs subcommittee on oversight and investigations <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> and other lawmakers have long urged the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to impose strict drug and alcohol standards instead of leaving it up individual utilities. <PERSON> Zech </PERSON>, under heavy criticism from both Democrats and Republicans on the subcommittee, stressed that the `` fitness for duty'' rule was simply a proposal and could be changed to include specific alcohol standards before it is issued next year. But he defended the commission's decision to remove strict alcohol provisions that were in earlier drafts of the regulation. <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> said it was more difficult to develop a consensus on alcohol standards than drug restrictions, noting the different blood alcohol levels used by various states and federal agencies to determine inebriation. Trying to include specific alcohol requirements in the rule could have delayed the final regulation `` another few months or maybe longer,'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> said. But lawmakers were befuddled and angered by that explanation. `` You're sitting around and waiting for -LRB- utility companies -RRB- to tell you how to do it,'' said Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>. `` Do n't you have some idea what the minimum standard ought to This is not a new subject.'' Rep. <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, a Republican who is often at odds with the Democrats' criticism, agreed with <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>. `` I think your judgment needs to be questioned,'' he told the commissioners. `` It just does n't make sense'' not to include the alcohol provision, he said. <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> pointed to an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> document that concluded that alcohol abuse and drinking-related problems `` are judged to present a vastly more pervasive work place problem than does drug abuse.'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> said he agreed with that statement, but another commissioner said drug abuse presented a bigger problem than alcohol because he believes drug use is more difficult to notice. Commissioner <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, a former submarine commander, said he `` threw people out of the submarine force for a first -LRB- drug -RRB- offense when everybody else said that was the wrong thing to do. I did n't ever throw anybody out for being drunk because I could tell when a guy was drunk and I did n't put him in a sensitive position.'' `` That may be the problem,'' <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said. `` We're very tolerant of being intoxicated as a society.''
