<HEAD>Four Senators Seeking Safety Review Of Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators are seeking an independent safety review of the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION> after disclosures that up to 30 major mishaps over three decades went unreported and in the wake of an equipment failure that released radioactive gas into the air. The escape Thursday of less than 0.01 millirems of tritium gas into the atmosphere posed no health threat, said plant spokeswoman <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Craft </PERSON>. A millirem is a measure of radiation; a routine chest X-ray totals about 20 millirems, according to Ms. Craft. Workers at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government-owned plant, the nation's sole producer of weapons-grade plutonium and tritium, were not evacuated. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, Sens. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore., called Thursday for an investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION>, which was established by Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> to give independent assessments of operations at nuclear At the state Capitol in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, 60 miles to the northeast, a dozen people held a two-hour vigil to demonstrate their concern. But in downtown <PERSON> Aiken </PERSON>, most of the customers at <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s beauty and barber shop said Thursday they were unconcerned about problems at the nearby plant `` Everybody's nonchalant who comes in the shop