<HEAD>Workers Demonstrate Against Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ About 800 street cleaners and garbage collectors demonstrated in front of City Hall to protest their firings by newly-appointed Mayor <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Christophe </PERSON>, Radio Haiti-Inter reported. Other municipal employees joined the demonstrators Thursday and went on strike, saying the mayor had no right to fire poor people and was incompetent, the radio said. Ms. <PERSON> Christophe </PERSON> accused the garbage-truck drivers of being followers of ousted Mayor <PERSON> Franck </PERSON> <PERSON> Romain </PERSON>, who is reputed to be a leader of the dreaded <ORGANIZATION> Tonton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macoutes </ORGANIZATION>, the feared henchmen of the <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> regime. <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> is suspected of being a mastermind of the Sept. 11 attack on the St. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> church that left 12 dead and more than 70 wounded. Rank-and-file soldiers named the massacre at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosco </ORGANIZATION> as one of the reasons for the Sept. 17 revolt in which they overthrew Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>, now in exile, was replaced by Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>. The flamboyant Ms. <PERSON> Christophe </PERSON>, a money-lender and owner of a chain of lottery shops, was named to replace <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> by the rank-and-file soldiers who engineered the coup. She accused the garbage collectors Thursday of having stolen 6,000 gallons of gasoline and 50 of the city's 56 garbage trucks, and of switching old tires for new ones and selling them. In another incident Thursday, several hundred demonstrators briefly blocked traffic on the highway between the capital and the International Airport. The demonstrators were protesting their expulsion Tuesday from what they claim to be state-owned lands abandoned by dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> when he was ousted in February 1986. One person was killed and three wounded when soldiers from the Presidential Guard expelled the squatters. Radio <PERSON> Soleil </PERSON> said five soldiers were seen among the demonstrators, apparently expressing solidarity with the protest. Also Thursday, troops dispersed several dozen people in <LOCATION> Port-de-Daix </LOCATION>, a northern port town, who demonstrated against allegedly incompetent government officials, <PERSON> Haiti-Inter </PERSON> said.
