<HEAD>Aerial Spraying Begins Three-Part Attack Against Medfly
Infestation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Overnight aerial spraying to kill a <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> fruit fly infestation left much of the city's <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> looking like <PERSON> Christo </PERSON> artwork, as residents wrapped cars, playground equipment and other belongings in plastic. Pesticide-laden helicopters criss-crossed a 35-square-mile area until early today in the first step of an all-out attack against the Medfly, an agricultural pest that destroys about 250 varieties of produce. The insecticide Malathion poses no health risk, agriculture officials said, but they warned residents that the sticky corn syrup in which it was mixed to attract the flies could damage a car's paint. The alert prompted a run on tarpaulins and plastic wrap at stores throughout the area. `` People say a lot of chain stores are out of the stuff,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Culver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hardware </LOCATION>. The effect of the protective measures was especially striking at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Art </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>, where outdoor sculptures swathed in black plastic and tape recalled fences and bridges transformed into artworks through similar wrapping by <PERSON> Christo </PERSON>, the Bulgarian-born artist. The spraying was ordered because 47 Medflies were found in the Palms area since Sept. 26, agricultural officials said. But aerial spraying was only the first step in the three-part attack against the pest, said <PERSON> Gera </PERSON> <PERSON> Curry </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. A quarantine against transporting fruit and vegetables from the area is expected to go into effect today or Monday, she said. The final step will be the release of millions of sterile Medflies later this month so that the wild Medflies that survived the spraying will, in effect, breed themselves out of existence. Although agricultural production in the urbanized area is slight, officials termed the infestation serious, saying it would threaten the state's $ 15.5 billion-a-year farm economy if allowed to spread. Along with parts of <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, the helicopters sprayed sections of west <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and the adjacent municipalities of <LOCATION> Culver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. About 100,000 people live in the sprayed area, which includes middle-class homes and apartments, multimillion-dollar mansions, swank shops and luxury car dealerships. For much of the day, Ms. <PERSON> Curry </PERSON> said, worried residents flooded hot lines set up by agriculture officials with questions about the spraying. At <ORGANIZATION> Paulee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Body </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shop </ORGANIZATION>, president <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleiner </PERSON> assigned four employees to cover more than 180 mostly high-priced automobiles parked outdoors. <PERSON> Fleiner </PERSON> said he spent about $ 500 on plastic and $ 200 on masking tape for the job, which took hours. At <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, a caravan of about 100 shiny Caddies left the sales lot Wednesday night for an underground parking lot at a bank building six blocks away, sales manager <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said Thursday.
