<HEAD>Diplomats Say Burma is Pariah</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with diplomats saying Burma's
government snubbed by other nations; picks up 3rd graf pvs `Thakin
Soe...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign nations are shunning <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s three-week-old military government that has cracked down on a popular uprising for democracy, diplomats said today The main official contacts have involved notes from several foreign embassies decrying the bloodshed since Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> seized power in a coup. The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said no nation has sent the standard message of congratulations to the new leader, which would signify recognition of his government. Diplomats also said <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, who also serves as the new foreign minister, has met no heads of foreign missions. Ambassadors of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> last month presented protest notes citing the killing of unarmed civilians by troops. Other countries, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, have expressed concern from their capitals. Meanwhile, state radio reported Thursday that two more opposition groups have registered with the government, bringing to seven the number of opposition parties that have surfaced since <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> seized power. The newest parties to register with the election commission were the <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, led by former communist rebel <PERSON> Thakin </PERSON> <PERSON> Soe </PERSON>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Fascist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, headed by onetime member of parliament <PERSON> Bo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kya </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyunt </PERSON>. <PERSON> Thakin </PERSON> <PERSON> Soe </PERSON>, 80, once led the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> communist </ORGANIZATION> rebels who followed a radical, Trotskyite program but were defeated by the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> military in the 1960s. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which registered earlier, also is headed by a former communist figure. The new military government, which seized power in Sept. 18, crushed pro-democracy demonstrations but announced that multi-party elections would be held in about three months. Although seven parties have registered with the commission, none have stated clearly whether they would take part in the elections, which also will be contested by the government's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Diplomats and other analysts are skeptical that fair elections can be held given a hardline government that has been willing to shoot thousands of unarmed demonstrators to stay in power. By official count, about 440 people have been killed since the military coup. Western diplomats here believe the death toll is much higher. Other anti-government groups are the <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youths </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>. The patron of an eighth anti-government group _ the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> _ is Nu, the former prime minister overthrown by strongman Ne Win in 1962. Western diplomats say they are convinced the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is fully supported by <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> and his military government, but that the new leaders want their actions to appear legal so as to subdue strong anti-government feelings among the public. Since last fall, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> has been wracked by bloody protests and a deteriorating economy. Demonstrators have called for the end of authoritarian rule and a liberalized economy to pull one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s most resource-rich nations out of poverty <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have temporarily frozen aid to <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> but have refrained from direct interference in the domestic turmoil. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced today <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would provide <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> with $ 450,000 in emergency food aid through <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> because of serious shortages. But Foreign Minister <PERSON> Sosuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> stressed at a news conference that `` This does n't mean we approve of <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s military government.''
