<HEAD>Radicals Clash With Riot Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radical students calling for the overthrow of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo hurled hundreds of firebombs and rocks at riot police today during a violent demonstration at a <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> college. In another demonstration in the southern city of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, about 300 students clashed with riot troopers and 12 troopers were injured, the <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. Police reported no arrests or serious injuries during the 90-minute clash in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, the largest in the capital in recent weeks. Some 2,000 students from about 30 colleges took part in the rally on the outskirts of southern <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to denounce the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> administration and call for the expulsion of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` Down with the fascist regime which suppresses the masses,'' the students chanted. `` Yankee go home.'' The leaders charged that the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> administration was a front for military rule and insisted there had been no democratic reforms in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, a former general who won presidential elections in December, has helped introduce broad democratic reforms since taking power. He has pledged to end authoritarian rule and make <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> a full democracy. The students marched out of the school and clashed on the highway outside with hundreds of riot police. Police armored vans with multiple tear gas launchers fired barrages of tear gas canisters. The two-hour riot in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> took place at the <ORGANIZATION> Chonam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> reported. The South Korean agency said the 12 troopers were injured by firebombs and rocks. The radicals have virtually