<HEAD>President Aquino Inspects Scandal-Tainted Dig</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> visited one of the country's most historic shrines today to decide whether to allow an American firm continue a controversial treasure hunt there. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> told reporters she was `` very pleased'' with the restoration of chambers unearthed by nearly a year of digging at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, a 16th Century Spanish fortress used by Japanese troops as a concentration camp for American and Filipino prisoners during World War II. She added that she and her staff need more time to determine whether to renew for a third time the digging permit given the firm <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Precious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev </LOCATION>. The firm's head, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> McDougal </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Soriano </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s chief security adviser, insist that tons of gold bullion are buried beneath the fort. They claim core drillings have yielded gold particles. The digging has been dogged by controversy since shortly after it began secretly in November. The treasure hunt became public in February when two Filipino workers were killed in a cave-in. Last month, the government's anti-graft prosecutor accused <PERSON> Soriano </PERSON> of accepting payments from the company. <PERSON> Soriano </PERSON> admitted he deposited a total $ 110,000 of company funds in his personal bank account but claimed it was simply entrusted to him pending a company reorganization. <PERSON> Soriano </PERSON> said the funds included $ 40,000 as a guarantee against damages to the fort, built by Spanish colonialists at the mouth of the <LOCATION> Pasig </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to defend the