<HEAD>Editorial Reactions on Bentsen-Quayle Debate</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Following is a roundup of editorial reaction to the vice presidential debate from newspapers around the country:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>St. Louis Post-Dispatch</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> accomplished three tasks with the most memorable line of Wednesday night's vice-presidential debate, when he told <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, ` Senator, you're no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.' With that remark, he helped establish himself as by far the better of the two candidates _ and in a close presidential election, he may have given many <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrats </PERSON> as good a reason as they need to come back to the fold next month.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` If -LRB- <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> -RRB- had only one decent answer to the question he faced at least three times _ the one about what he would do if a tragedy thrust him into the presidency _ we would have been more reassured. But obviously he either had n't anticipated the question or did n't want to answer it. ... `` He would say a prayer for himself and the country. Good. He would call together the Cabinet. Good. But then what? Sen. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> prefered to talk about his qualifications rather than give us a clue that he had a thoughtful plan in mind.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Star Tribune (Minneapolis)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` The ` debate' seemed to confirm the awfulness of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to choose <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as running mate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' choice looked better; -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was more polished, more experienced, more adept at ripostes like his now-famous slashing of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s self-comparison with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> But the erratic proceedings Wednesday night offered little basis for solid comparison. It was an opportunity wasted.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>The Atlanta Constitution</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Nothing in Mr. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s performance provided reassurance that he is ready to stand on the verge of the presidency or that Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> acted with then-unrecognized wisdom in selecting him. ... `` Mr. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> _ no surprise _ was the cooler, cannier head, in part simply because of his greater experience.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Arkansas Gazette (Little Rock)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Quayle, in our view, was mechanical in his responses to the panel's questions, reverting on several occasions to the same phraseology about his qualifications regardless of the question asked _ a reflection of briefings and rehearsals. ... `` <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> presented a mature and thoughtful figure, drawing a sharp contrast with <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on relative leadership qualities and experience. Relative ages may have been a factor, perhaps depending upon the viewer's generation, but <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s broader experience clearly testified to his benefit.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Charleston (W.Va.) Gazette</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Wednesday's vice presidential debate wo n't be remembered for exchanges about Social Security, farm subsidies or foreign policy. `` The debate turned on one question: is <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> qualified to be president should anything happen to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>? Three times, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s junior senator was asked how he would handle such a crisis. Three times, he faltered.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dallas Times Herald:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Sen. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> stood up fairly well to some tough, maybe even unfair questioning. He did not fall on his face, as some pundits had expected, but he never gave a satisfactory answer to three questions about what he would do first if he became president. But at the same time, Sen. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> proved that he not only is a knowledgeable, articulate officeholder who has a solid record of achievement, but that he can be awfully tough in the clutch.''
