<FIRST>r a PM-RadonHome     10-07 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radon Home,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Radon Levels In Clinton Home Are Highest Ever Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tests on a home that had radon levels about 800 times higher than the federal safety standard have failed to convince some neighbors that the colorless, odorless gas could kill them, officials said. The test last week on an unidentified home may be the highest radon levels ever measured in a structure. `` We believe it's the highest that anyone's ever found,'' said <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Daggett </PERSON>, acting commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>. Officials said that 59 of the 74 other nearby homes in the rural community about 40 miles west of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> also showed unsafe radon levels. Many homes that have registered high radon readings sit above the Reading Prong, a belt of uranium that stretches from <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> across northeastern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The federal standard for structures is 4 picocuries, a unit of measurement for radioactivity. Federal officials say exposure to high levels of the naturally occurring gas may cause up to 20,000 lung cancer deaths a year _ essentially all those not caused from smoking. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuys </PERSON>, an investigator for the <ORGANIZATION> Hunterdon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, spent the weekend knocking on doors in the sprawling development, urging residents to place charcoal-filled canisters in their basements for testing. He said he met with some distrustful and suspicious residents _ and several slammed doors. Some were only convinced of the urgency because it was important enough to get a government employee working on a Saturday. When a sampling of residents were told Thursday of the state's findings, some said they did n't know much about radon, some said they did n't care much, and some said they did n't care to talk about the levels found in their homes Others said they have had their homes tested or are awaiting test results. Officials said that although a radon test only costs about $ 10, and a high level is easily cured with a ventilation system for about $ 1,200, apathy is the biggest challenge in fighting the health problem. They also say that many residents may ignore warnings because they have grown immune to the constant stream of warnings about environmental problems. The announcement about the <LOCATION> Clinton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION> home comes about two years after state officials discovered 105 houses with elevated radon levels in a nearby development. <PERSON> Daggett </PERSON> said the barrage of testing here began after a homeowner did a routine radon test and found a reading of about 200 picocuries. The department confirmed the results and began testing other homes. <PERSON> Daggett </PERSON> said the home with the highest reading registered more than 3,000 picocuries. The federal safety standard of 4 picocuries is the equivalent of smoking one-half pack of cigarettes a day, or having 200 to 300 chest X-rays per year. It also is the concentration that would increase the chance of getting lung cancer by 1 percent for a lifetime resident.
</TEXT>
