<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Transplants     10-07 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Transplants,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Reports First Case Of AIDS From Transplant _ An '84 Bone
Operation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS-Heterosexuals, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal health officials have reported the first case of AIDS acquired from a transplant operation, but researchers stressed that the operation was four years ago _ before the advent of AIDS testing. Transplant patients have previously been infected with the virus that causes AIDS, but Thursday's report from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> marked the first time AIDS virus has been associated with a bone transplant, and the first case ever reported in which any kind of transplant has resulted in AIDS itself. `` This is consistent with how we have found the virus to be transmitted previously _ in blood, bodily fluids and body parts from another individual. ... It's an expected mode of transmission,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, an AIDS specialist with the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> noted that the surgery in question took place before the advent of antibody testing for AIDS; the donor was an intravenous drug user infected with AIDS. `` It's important for the lay public to understand that this case occurred in 1984. ... The donor could not be screened,'' he said. Since then, AIDS tests have become available, and the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has recommended that all donors of tissue or organs be tested for AIDS infection. This first AIDS-transplant case occurred in a woman with progressive spinal disease who, in November 1984, underwent a spinal fusion using bone from her hospital's bone bank. In February 1988, she was diagnosed with AIDS. She was a health care worker, but there were no indications she had contracted an AIDS infection on the job, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reported. The donor from whom the bone came, a 52-year-old man who had undergone a partial hip bone removal, turned out to be an intravenous drug user, and thus at high risk for AIDS. He was diagnosed with AIDS less than two years after the woman's surgery and died in 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s parent agency, recommended Thursday that living donors of bone be tested for AIDS at the time the bone is removed, and then again 90 days later to ensure that any AIDS infection is detected. More than 74,000 AIDS cases have been reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with more than 42,000 deaths so far, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. Some 24 cases of AIDS virus transmission through transplants have been reported worldwide, in cases such as kidney, liver and heart transplants, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. None of those patients has been diagnosed with AIDS itself, but `` undoubtedly, some will develop AIDS in the future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
