<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two public opinion polls published today showed a tie between the dovish <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, and the two rivals swapped accusations in a series of television advertisements. Results of those questioned in the two polls showed Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> would win 42 seats each in the 120-member parliament if the Nov. 1 election were held today. The results were published in the <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. The 1984 elections ended in a stalemate with neither of the major political blocs able to form a coalition. The result was shared rule in a national unity government with Labor leader <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> each serving two years as premier. The Likud-sponsored Dahaf poll predicted <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> and its right-wing allies would win 60 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>, while Labor and the left secured an equal number. The Labor-sponsored Decima poll said Labor and the leftist lists would gain a narrow majority of 61 seats. The Dahaf poll questioned 662 voters, and the <ORGANIZATION> Decima </ORGANIZATION> poll encompassed 1,000 voters. The paper did not disclose the margin of error given, and the offices of both pollsters were closed for the Jewish Sabbath. Also today, American-born Rabbi <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahane </PERSON> appealed to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> requesting it overturn a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> decision to disqualify his anti-Arab party from running in the elections The parliamentary committee barred <PE