 After years of public protests, the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> legislature has agreed to make Lithuanian the Baltic republic's official language and to permit display of religious symbols, an activist reported today The decision prompted an estimated 100,000 Lithuanians, mostly Roman Catholics, to gather in their capital, <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>, this morning to celebrate with nationalist songs, flag-waving and dancing, said activist <PERSON> Vytautas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogusis </PERSON>. Also today, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official Soviet news agency, reported that the legislature of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, another <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> republic </LOCATION>, was drafting a bill to make Latvian the republic's official language. Similar measures were adopted earlier in the third <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, in response to a campaign by nationalists. <PERSON> Bogusis </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, a group demanding an end to Soviet control over their republic, said local newspapers today reprinted decrees of the Presidium, or executive committee of the legislature. One measure allows display of religious symbols, and another designates Lithuanian the republic's official language Many Baltic activists complain that top officials in their republics do not know the indigenous languages and that Russian and other tongues are contaminating their language. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> also reported adoption of Lithuanian as the official language and said <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> flags could now be displayed at gatherings, sporting events, song and dance festivals. The dispatch did not say whether the flag was the one that flew in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> before it was incorporated into the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, or whether it was the flag of Soviet <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. Lithuanians in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> said they believed the order applies to the independence flag, which had been banned. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> took over <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> in 1940 under a secret pact with <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Activists are demanding that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> renounce the pact. <PERSON> Bogusis </PERSON> said activists raised the yellow, green and red independence flag today atop Gediminas Tower on the square where the demonstration took place. Many people singing the nationalist songs and dancing also carried the flag, he said. Police, who earlier would have torn down the flag and arrested nationalist demonstrators, did not interfere, <PERSON> Bogusis </PERSON> said.
