<HEAD>Pinochet Rejects Calls To Resign Early</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE casualty report, ADDS
background. Pickup 12th graf pvs, ``The constitution...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> rejected demands that he resign as president before his term expires in 1990 and said the military will continue to play a key role in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s future The 72-year-old ruler spoke to the nation after police armed with clubs fired water cannons and tear gas at crowds who swarmed the streets Thursday to celebrate <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s defeat in a national referendum. Police said today that two people were killed in the demonstrations, including a 14-year-old boy shot by unidentified attackers and a 31-year-old robber shot by police. Unknown assailants shot two other people, who were in serious condition today, police said. Eight officers were injured, one seriously, and 58 demonstrators were detained and later released, police said. The capital was calm this morning after street scuffles between roving bands of youths and police in jeeps and water trucks lasted until midnight. In his first public statement since the Wednesday ballot, which he lost by a margin of more than 11 percent, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> declared Thursday night: `` I recognize and accept the majority verdict expressed yesterday by the citizenry.'' According to the terms of an 8-year-old constitution, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remains in power until March 1990, when he will be succeeded by the winner of open elections planned for late next year. Pinohet is not barred from running in the election. He has not indicated whether he plans to run. Reading from a text, the 72-year-old <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> warned the opposition that its plans to amend the existing constitution to speed up his departure would be in vain. `` No one can feel they have the mandate of the people to twist what the people decided,'' he said, in reference to the constitution, which was approved by voters in 1980 in a loosely staged vote that critics complain was rife with fraud. Wednesday's vote was well-organized, massively attended and free of charges of fraud or violence. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> expressed `` the deep pride I feel at the civic maturity with which each one of you faced this act of singular importance.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was dressed in his white dress general's uniform for the taped speech, broadcast nationwide on all television and radio stations. Triumphant opposition leaders Thursday vowed to press their demands for <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to allow quick elections and step down soon. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> seized power in the 1973 coup that toppled elected President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist. `` An authoritarian system has been overthrown,'' said Socialist <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, a director of a 16-party coalition that led the campaign for <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s defeat. `` It is indispensable now to elect, within a short period of time, a president and a congress with powers to modify the constitution.'' But the opposition faces the challenge of maintaining its unity. Potentially divisive issues such as human rights trials and the future of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> could sow dissent while opposition leaders negotiate with the armed forces to speed the transition to full democracy. Political maneuvering by top opposition figures for nomination to the presidency also is expected to influence relations among the parties in the coalition. The constitution, drawn up by the <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> administration, calls for electing a congress in a year. But its provisions leave the legislature virtually powerless to pass amendments. It also gives the armed forces autonomy and an influential role in national policy-making. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, leader of the army, said the military `` will be the guide in building the future <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>.'' Early Thursday, small groups of government opponents descended on downtown to celebrate the referendum result. They were quickly joined by tens of thousands of others, mostly youths, who virtually took control of many streets and some avenues in the city's center, marching and chanting `` <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, go away'' and `` He has fallen.'' Police only occasionally broke up the early demonstrations, but the protesters later became more strident and police began using more force. When the demonstrators began throwing rocks, bottles and sticks at officers, riot-control squads responded with water cannons and tear gas in running street battles.
</TEXT>
