 Two men who admitted setting fire to a house suspected of being used to deal cocaine have been acquitted by a jury, leading city officials to warn against vigilante action. Jury foreman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said Thursday's verdict was a way of telling city officials more has to be done to fight drugs. `` I imagine the verdict does send out a message in two directions _ to the mayor and to the Police Department that more has to be done about crack houses,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> were found innocent after a two-day trial. They admitted setting the fire, saying they feared for the safety of children in their neighborhood. `` I hope this verdict sends no message,'' Presiding Judge <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON> told the jurors. `` It applies to the facts only in this case.'' But some jurors said they cleared <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Kent </ORGANIZATION> because <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s drug problem could cause people to take extreme measures. `` -LRB- I -RRB- would have probably done the same thing. No. I would have been more violent,'' juror <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandemer </PERSON> said. The charges stemmed from fires in October and November 1987 at an abandoned house allegedly occupied by drug dealers who the defendants testified had turned their quiet, working-class neighborhood into a place of fear. `` They were laughing at the neighborhood,'' <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> testified. Defense attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Steingold </PERSON> said residents of the neighborhood were continually frightened by the sound of gunfire. <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> said they started the fires after police failed to investigate complaints filed by them and other residents. Law enforcement authorities said they do n't condone vigilantism and will take all possible measures to prevent such activity. <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hair </PERSON> said he `` will not permit law-abiding citizens to break the law on the theory that they're frustrated ... Vigilantism simply will not be tolerated.
