<HEAD>Gunman Pleads Guilty to Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A weeping <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> pleaded guilty today to six counts of kidnapping in the Feb. 2 takeover of a private school and was sentenced to one life term, plus five 20-year terms. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> clutched a red-bound Bible as Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karrh </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> asked him how he pleaded to each count. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> nodded and said softly, `` Guilty.'' The pleas came in the third day of <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s trial on 110 counts of kidnapping. The other counts were dropped in exchange for his guilty pleas. He could have faced up to 10,000 years in prison. <PERSON> Karrh </PERSON> told <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> his sentences would run concurrently and that he would recommend <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> get psychiatric treatment in the prison system. `` I think you need treatment,'' the judge told <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, who sat in a chair during the sentencing. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> had been charged with kidnapping 110 people at gunpoint at the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> End </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> had been defending himself in state court here as a crusader for people's constitutional rights A second man, described by police as an unwilling accomplice, testified Thursday he was duped by <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> into helping take over the school and later was threatened with his life if he tried to back out. Two of <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s sisters, <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION>, had met with him last night and today to try to talk him into pleading guilty. `` I begged him to go to prison,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. `` At least he will have part of his life.'' She said her brother was mentally and physically exhausted. She said he was suffering from a cold and had lost 20 pounds in the eight months since the school takeover. Sheriff <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, who with five of his deputies guarded <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> during the sentencing, said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> would be returned to <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> authorities for transfer to prison.
