<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Locusts,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudan Stops Frontier Locust-Spraying; Blames Ethiopian Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> said Friday it has stopped trying to control a locust plague along the Ethiopian border because of military attacks. The defense minister says no one has been hurt in the assaults on villages and spray planes, but he said vehicles were burned in an air attack on a convoy near <LOCATION> Kassala </LOCATION>, 260 miles east of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>. He said the government has asked the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> government to stop the attacks. The episode appeared to be a major setback to <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>'s efforts to deal with one of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s worst locust infestations in years. In <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> capital, officials refused comment on the situation. Relations between <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> have been strained for several years, especially since a rebellion broke out in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> in 1983. <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> of arming, financing and harboring the rebels. <PERSON> Addis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ababa </PERSON> alleges that <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> allows several anti-Ethiopian guerrilla groups to maintain official, open presence in the Sudanese capital. The official <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Syd </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, announced the decision to abandon the frontier spraying operation. `` All locust control operations along the Sudanese-Ethiopian borders were completely halted due to the shelling of the pest control areas by the Ethiopian air force,'' the news agency said. It quoted <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> as saying that sprayers and others involved with the program already were withdrawn. Swarms of the crop-devouring insects appeared in several <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> countries in recent weeks after heavy rains created perfect breeding conditions. In <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, swarms have occurred mainly in the eastern and western regions, but one massive swarm hit crops in the <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> area and others are expected. The government committed 22 planes to the spraying operation, but officials say three wo n't fly and one crashed in the western sector. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Issa </PERSON>, minister of state at the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, told the newspaper Al-Ayam that two Ethiopian MiG jet fighters attacked vehicles assigned to the crop-dusting operation in villages along the border. He said spray planes had come under fire from within <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. The armed forces newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Guwat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al-Musalaha </ORGANIZATION> confirmed the reports on Thursday. `` The Ethiopian air force intercepted a locust spray convoy last week in the eastern region ... and hit some cars working in the spray operation,'' the newspaper said. `` No one was hurt.'' Defense Minister <PERSON> Abdel-Meguid </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> told Al-Guwat Al-Musalaha the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had relayed <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s demand that <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> `` stop violating Sudanese air space'' so that `` we work together ... to eradicate locusts, which affect all the countries in the region including <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>.''
