<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that it has suspended <ORGANIZATION> Recognition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> from bidding on contracts, pending outcome of a criminal case against the company and two of its top executives. REI, Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and vice president <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON> were indicted Thursday by a federal grand jury in connection with an unsuccessful plot to rig bids on $ 400 million worth of postal automation contracts. Assistant Postmaster General <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Davin </PERSON>, in charge of procurement, announced the suspension, which bans the company and its subsidiaries from bidding on postal contracts for 120 days, and can be extended pending resolution of the charges against the company. Several relatively small contracts the company and its subsidiaries currently have with the postal service will not be affected, but can not be expanded or renewed. According to the indictment, the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> company's unsuccessful effort was allegedly engineered in 1986 with the help of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, vice-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s Board of Governors. The indictment charged that <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>, an unindicted co-conspirator, manipulated a <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decision over procuring sophisticated optical-character scanning equipment for sorting mail. After the procurement scheme came to light in 1986 with <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>' guilty plea to kickback and embezzlement charges, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGAN