<HEAD>Pope Seeks to Influence Thinking About Europe in French Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> will use the pulpit of three international institutions to advance his view of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> at a time when the region is divided about its future political identity. On a four-day trip to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> that starts Saturday, the pope will speak to the Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, all in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>. The agreement by Common Market countries to fully integrate their economies in 1992 has touched off widespread debate about whether <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> should move toward becoming a single political unit. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> raised a storm of protest last month when she declared that a U.S.-style European union would be `` highly damaging'' to the individual states. Several European countries and Common Market organs charged that her comments were a roadblock to a long-desired goal of unity. Against the backdrop of this debate, the Polish-born <PERSON> pope </PERSON> is expected to elaborate on his own vision of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ one united by Christianity and stretching `` from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to the Urals.'' A <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> official said the pope wanted to address the three international institutions because they pondered the direction of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` I think he -LRB- the pope -RRB- feels very strongly that in the process of reflection on the future of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the church's voice should be there,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has expounded on the theme several times. In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1982, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> called on <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to return to the Christian principles that tied it together as in medieval days. `` You can still be the beacon of civilization and stimulate progress throughout the world,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> the next year, he said Christianity had formed the basis for political systems built on respect for human rights. The pope felt so strongly about a common European heritage that he released an encyclical in 1985 honoring two ninth century saints who brought Christianity to the Slavs. In <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s view, Saints <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Methodius </ORGANIZATION> forged a link between the Eastern Orthodox and Western Roman Catholic traditions. `` Part of his reflection on the Christian roots of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is to encourage a revival of Christianity,'' the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> official said. The pope has expressed particular concern about the church in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Although over 80 percent of French citizens are Roman Catholics, less than 20 percent attend Mass, according to French public opinion polls. This trip, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s fourth to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, will include visits to the dioceses of <ORGANIZATION> Metz </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Mulhouse </LOCATION> in the northeast near <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In addition, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> will salute <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> on its 2,000 th birthday The city, which changed hands between <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for centuries, has a blend of cultures that has attracted groups promoting <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> unity. The Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, composed of 21 parliamentary democracies, aims to coordinate European legislation through accords. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> hears alleged violations of the Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s main treaty, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> is the parliamentary assembly of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>.
