<FIRST>u w AM-UsedOil     10-07 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Used Oil,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Strikes Down EPA Policy on Labeling of Oil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court on Friday struck down an <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> policy not to list used oil collected for recyling as hazardous waste. At issue was <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision in 1986 that a hazardous-waste designation would only create a stigma and discourage many locations such as gasoline stations from collecting used oil for recycling. But a three-judge panel of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here said that factor can not be taken into account, particularly when <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> had already concluded that a broad category of used oils were hazardous wastes. `` The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> erroneously based its decision not to list recycled oils as hazardous wastes on the stigmatic effects of such a listing, a factor not permitted by the statute,'' the court said. It ordered <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to determine if recycled oils `` meet the technical criteria for listing'' as hazardous wastes. `` I would consider this a major victory'' to clean up `` billions of gallons of used oil,'' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. She predicted that the court's decision will force <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to declare broad categories of used oil hazardous wastes because the agency's own studies have documented that it contains many toxic chemicals. `` The court's action should force <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to stop the dumping of waste oil into municipal landfills and lead to better treatment an reclamation of the oil,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Case </PERSON>, general counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> Hazardous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The decision `` means <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> should be more concerned about the stigma of harm to the environment than the stigma of calling recycled oil a hazardous waste,'' said Case, whose organization represents large waste-disposal companies. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> attorney, said the court ruling `` arguably leaves a lot of discretion to the agency to determine whether certain oils are hazardous.'' She said the agency was studying the ruling and had not decided how to proceed. In 1985, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> proposed to list a broad category of used automotive and industrial oils as hazardous wastes. But it backed off in 1986, after receiving nearly 800 comments from gasoline dealers and other recyclers. The agency deferred any decision on used oil generally but decided not to list oil collected for recycling as hazardous waste. `` The effect of listing would create such a stigma in the used oil recycling industry that many recycling sources woudl simply refuse to take used oil,'' <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> decided that `` the used oil might then be diverted to less environmentally sound management options such as throwing it down the sewer,'' she said. The appeals court said `` EPA's concern over the possible adverse environmental consequences of listing used oil may well be warranted,'' but such views `` can not override the intent of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> clearly expressed in the language and structure of the statute.'' `` It is the agency's obligation to comply with the dictates of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and ours to enforce them,'' a three-judge panel said in an opinion by Circuit Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> that was joined by Judges <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Re </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` carefully separated the listing decision from the resultant regulatory decisions,'' <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> wrote, and a 1985 law enacted to prod <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to take action `` simply requires the agency to determine whether to list used oil as hazardous.'' `` Only after the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> decides to list does the statute permit it to consider the effect of its regulations on recycling,'' he wrote. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 1.2 billion gallons of used oil is produced annually, but only half is recycled, said <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, another attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` The laundry list of substances that have been found in used oil is alarming,'' she said. These include benzene, <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> and heavy metals such as lead, cadmium and chromium. In a separate opinion issued Friday, the appeals court panel upheld <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s rules governing the burning of hazardous waste and used oil.
