<SECOND>AM-Chile-Candidates,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Potential Presidential Candidates Rose Before Pinochet's Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Veteran politicians who rose to prominence before Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> seized power 15 years ago dominate the field of potential candidates for a presidential election next year. In the opposition, which includes parties from the left to the center-right, a few younger leaders who made important contributions to the fight against the authoritarian president also are among possible nominees. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, 72, would be the top contender on the right if he decides to run. The constitution allows him to be a candidate, but he has not announced his plans. On Wednesday, Chileans voted in a referendum to reject <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s bid to extend his rule until 1997, clearing the way for an election in December 1989. <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, moderate politicians who led the opposition campaign for the referendum, are the strongest contenders in the opposition. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest, is a seasoned politican and former senator who played a key role in the tumultuous days before the 1973 coup in which <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> toppled the elected government of <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Allende </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> was the main spokesman for the 16-party coalition that campaigned against <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> in the referendum, and he received more publicity than most of his peers. In a massively attended final campaign rally, he delivered a forceful and eloquent speech that showed his oratory skills. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, a 67-year-old law professor, is more widely accepted by conservative sectors than <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> and other prominent opposition leaders. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>, 50, a moderate socialist economist and lawyer, is a relative newcomer to politics. He was catapulted to national prominence by his dramatic performance in a campaign television debate. In the debate, the charismatic, tough-talking <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> challenged <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> personally, staring into the camera and shaking his finger. Never before during <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s rule had television shown such a scene. But many consider <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>' socialist ideas and his connections with the Allende government offensive to center-right groups in the opposition. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> was a middle-ranking official for the Allende administration. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> have denied any presidential ambitions and said the opposition needs an all-out effort to agree on a single candidate to lead a `` government of national unity'' after <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. `` It's too early to talk about candidates,'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> said Thursday in his first news conference after the opposition victory. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>, asked Friday about his possible presidential candidacy, replied: `` Is there going to be an election now? As far as I know, <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> is still pretty much alive and well.'' Many observers think <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> would have a better chance at nomination, especially if the opposition succeeds with plans to create a four-year transition government. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>' comparative youth gives him the option of waiting until a later election. Other dissident figures mentioned as potential candidates include <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdes </PERSON>, 66, and <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, 52. Both held Cabinet posts in the government of former president <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Frei </PERSON> in the 1960s, but they gained additional prominence in the years of opposition to <LOCATION> Pinochet </LOCATION>. The only civilian with prominence anywhere near <LOCATION> Pinochet </LOCATION>'s is <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Onofre </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarpa </PERSON>, a 67-year-old landowner and former senator with a reputation of being as fiercily anti-communist as <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. Few doubt that <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> himself could be nominated. Despite his defeat in the referendum, he still won 43 percent of the vote. `` He is the most important political figure in the country,'' said Interior Minister <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>. `` Few leaders in the world would be able to get such an extrordinary vote after 15 years in power.''
</TEXT>
