<HEAD>10,000 March On Montenegro's Parliament; Gov't Promises Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 10,000 people chanting `` You betrayed the people!'' demanded the resignation of local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders Friday in a march on a <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> republic's parliament, <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> radio reported In <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, the ruling Politburo issued a statement promising high-level personnel changes and the introduction of radical market-oriented economic reform in an effort to stem three months of unrest over economic and ethnic issues. The street rally in <LOCATION> Titograd </LOCATION>, in the republic of <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>, began after 1,000 construction workers stopped work to protest low wages and falling living standards, the radio report said. About 10,000 protesters then marched to the legislature, the radio said. Demonstrations also broke out in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> and in the city of <LOCATION> Krusevac </LOCATION>, the radio said. The protests came a day after an estimated 30,000 protesters stormed a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters and forced the resignation of party leaders in the autonomous province of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION>, in the Serbian republic. Serbian nationalists have led most recent protests, but the rallies are driven also by an economic crisis that has inflation at 217 percent, the foreign debt at $ 21 billion and unemployment at 15 percent. Friday's statement by the Politburo promised `` to make necessary personnel changes'' in an Oct. 17 meeting of the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` which should contribute to the more efficient work of that organ.'' The statement, carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency, also called for the introduction of a radical market-oriented economic reform next year. In a recent interview, Premier <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> mentioned a major reform of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s mixed economy. The reform, scheduled to be adopted Nov. 29 in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, will introduce more private businesses, allow majority foreign ownership of businesses and close or sell off money-losing state companies. The statement also promised a major reduction in government but did not elaborate. In <LOCATION> Krusevac </LOCATION>, 90 miles south of <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, several thousand workers demonstrated to demand higher wages and the ouster of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders, the radio said. In <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, 400 high school students from <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> marched on the national <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, chanting that the mainly Christian Serbs will never give up power in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, an autonomous province bordering <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. Mainly Moslem ethnic Albanians now make up 90 percent of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s population. The teen-agers, joined by <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> students, protested alleged harassment by Albanians. They were met at <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> by Vice President <PERSON> Spasoje </PERSON> <PERSON> Medenica </PERSON>, who listened to their grievances before they dispersed, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. Several dozen Communist party leaders have been attacked by name in recent rallies by Serbs. After the resignation of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> province's 15 Politburo members, the largely <ORGANIZATION> Albanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> party leadership in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> is expected to come under pressure to make sweeping changes at a meeting it holds Oct. 13. The resignations in <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> were a major victory for <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who wants more control over the two provinces. The Serbian leader's opponents suspect he is using the mass rallies to gain more national power for himself and for <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the largest of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics. Many Serbs see <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> as political heir to the late President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, who died in 1980 and left the nation with a complex system of annual rotation in the occupants of top political offices. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s advance alarms many politicians in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s other republics
</TEXT>
