<SECOND>AM-Hasenfus Suit,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Crash Victim Sues Secord, Hakim, Southern Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mercenary shot down in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> flying supplies to the Contras is suing Iran-Contra figures <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> for $ 135 million, saying they misled the crew and abandoned him during three months of captivity. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Marinette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, also sued <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION>, a shadowy, CIA-linked cargo airline, and <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which he identified as a shell company owned by <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and controlled by <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Thale </PERSON> denied Friday any connection with <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON>. The suit claimed the company paid his expenses. <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON> filed a similar suit in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> federal court in May, but jurisdiction questions are pending there because the planes allegedly flew out of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> are based. <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON>' plane was shot down over <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in 1986. He parachuted to safety, but three crewmen died. <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON> was tried by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> and sentenced to 30 years in prison, then sent back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after three months. <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Sally </PERSON>, said they were told the supply operation was a patriotic mission, but later found out <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> were profiting from the deal. He also said <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> promised help when he was captured, but never delivered. `` This guy was captured by the Sandinistas,'' said <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> `` What did he expect, that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military would step in and save him?'' The suit, filed Tuesday in federal court, says that <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON> was recruited in 1986 through <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> pilot. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, who later died in the crash, led <PERSON> Hasenfus </PERSON> to believe `` the Contra resupply operation was being run ` right out of the back door of the White House''' by <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, the suit said. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> major general, are accused with former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> figures <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> of conspiring to defraud the government by diverting proceeds from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> arms sales to the Contras at a time when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> banned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the rebels. <PERSON> Thale </PERSON> denied any relationship between <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, although <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> records in 1986 listed them at the same address.
