<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     10-07 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kurds Return To Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of 501 Kurdish refugees returned to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> voluntarily on Friday, two months after they fled and claimed that Iraqi forces dropped chemical bombs on their settlements. Regional Gov. <PERSON> Hayri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozakcioglu </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the Kurdish refugees, the second group to return, were transferred to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> from a southeastern border post in <LOCATION> Habur </LOCATION>. A group of 969 Kurdish refugees returned to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on Wednesday. The two groups were among 60,000 Kurds who were settled in five tent cities in southeastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> in August after they left <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. At the urging of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> proclaimed an amnesty for the Kurds. Before the first group returned, only two Kurds had taken advantage of the amnesty. The second group of Kurds was granted special status because the amnesty expired Thursday night, a Turkish government official said on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Kozakcioglu </PERSON> said some of the refugees at <LOCATION> Diyarbakir </LOCATION> tent city threw stones at the returnees Friday and tried to keep them from leaving. He said they called the returnees traitors and `` spies of the Iraqi regime.'' Police fired in the air and firefighters shot water to disperse the crowd. <PERSON> Kozakcioglu </PERSON> said two policemen and four Kurds were slightly injured. The Kurds traveled for 20 hours on buses and open trucks to the border. The government said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> gave assurances that the refugees would be safely settled in their villages. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> initially asked the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> to supervise the return, but the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> declined after <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> refused to grant its request for further guarantees on behalf of the refugees. The Kurds, 20 million people living in a region where borders of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> converge, have been fighting for independence for the past century. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> stepped up attacks on the Kurds soon after <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> agreed to a cease-fire in their eight-year war on Aug. 20. Security forces in the southeastern township of Uludere killed two Kurdish guerrillas in a clash, the regional governor's office said. The statement, carried by the semi-official <ORGANIZATION> Anatolia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said authorities told rebels to surrender and the guerrillas opened fire on Thursday. It said one guerrilla was captured. The suspects were responsible for killing a policeman and a village guard and wounding three soldiers in three different attacks. The guerrillas were believed to be members of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Kurdish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which wants to set up a Marxist state in parts of eastern and southeastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. More than 900 civilians and security personnel and an equal number of insurgents have been killed since the rebels started hit-and-run attacks in 1984, official reports say. Kurds make up about one-fifth of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s population of 52 million.
