<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Atomic Safety and <ORGANIZATION> Licensing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> vacated on Friday another <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> panel's decision to go forward with a full-power license for the <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear power plant on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, N.Y The appeal board found that the <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Licensing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> did not have the authority to remove state and local governments as intevenors in a case before a different panel, said <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopeck </PERSON>. Friday's ruling `` reverses that and at the same time, says all outstanding emergency planning issues have not been resolved,'' <PERSON> Kopeck </PERSON> said. `` Thus, the full-power license authorization does not exist and that authorization must be vacated,'' he said. In a 20-page decision, the three-judge appeals panel agreed with <PERSON> Shoreham </PERSON>'s owners that the state and local governments had `` obstructed the discovery process and failed to obey certain -LRB- licensing -RRB- board orders ... and that the only appropriate sanction is dismissal ...'' However, the licensing board only had authority to dismiss the governments in the case it was hearing, according to the appeals board. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lois </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the embattled $ 5.3 billion plant, said the company will fight Friday's ruling. `` Today's decision by the appeals board did not overrule the ... licensi