<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A felony court acquitted a Greek businessman of espionage Friday, although he admitted giving details of the U.S.-built Stinger anti-aircraft missile to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The three-member court said <PERSON> Michalis </PERSON> <PERSON> Megaloconomou </PERSON> was innocent on the ground the material handed over was not secret. `` Megaloconomou took unclassified materials for a well-known weapons system. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was n't going to build anything from material it already had obtained from other people,'' Prosecutor <PERSON> Constantinos </PERSON> <PERSON> Androulikakis </PERSON> said in his summing up. The 40-year-old businessman told the court he gave 400 microfiche cards to a Soviet intelligence agent in April 1984 but did n't know they contained information on the shoulder-fired Stinger's trigger system. `` I thought they contained information on a telephone system,'' he said. <PERSON> Megaloconomou </PERSON> also told the court he traveled to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1984 on a false passport and was given a miniature camera, decoding pads and a radio receiver by a Soviet agent. The case was linked with the May 1985 defection in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> of Soviet agent <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Bokhane </PERSON>, whose revelations cast doubts on <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s capacity to safeguard <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> secrets and delayed the sale of 40 U.S.-made jet fighters to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Brig. <PERSON> Ioannis </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexakis </PERSON>, a former head of counter-intelligence for the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, told the court Wednesday <PERSON> Megaloconomou </PERSON> had been a Soviet spy for 10 years when he was arrested in September 19