<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on Friday urged <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to begin trade and said it would drop trade barriers to promote ties with its communist rival. If <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> agrees, the trade will be treated as domestic commerce with no tariffs, <PERSON> Rha </PERSON> <PERSON> Woong-bae </PERSON>, the deputy prime minister and economic planning minister, told a news conference. He said the trade will not include military products. <PERSON> Rha </PERSON>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s top economic official, called for a quick start to trade both directly and through third nations. He also called for talks on working out details of the commerce, which he said would benefit both sides. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ally, has improved its trade and other relations with other communist nations, such as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rha </PERSON> listed coal, iron ore and corn as probable import items from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and steel and textiles as likely South Korean exports to the North. Any trade, either direct or through third nations, would depend on North Korean consent. There are no indications the North would accept trade with the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, and past efforts at improving relations have had little success. The countries do not have any contacts or ties beyond a single hotline. The border is sealed and both nations have been locked in a bitter confrontation for 40 years. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo this week called for a major effort to end the confrontation and work toward reunifying the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. Radical students have held violent demonstrations to press demands for reunification. The countries were split at the end of World War II. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the South in 1950 to start the Korean War, which ended with an armistice in 1953. Talks on improving relations are to resume Oct. 13 after deadlocking in August. The sides held five rounds of talks on economic cooperation in 1985, but the North stopped contacts in January 1986 to protest U.S.-South Korean military training exercises.
