<HEAD>Government Denies Amnesty International Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has denied <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s reports of political assassinations and political prisoners in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, saying they `` deform reality.'' The London-based human rights organization said Wednesday in its annual report that it continued to receive complaints from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> of arbitrary arrests and assassinations of members of groups frequently related to land disputes. `` Many assassinations were attributed to civilian gunmen linked to landowners but seemed to have the consent of the authorities,'' the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> released a communique Thursday saying the government expressed its `` absolute rejection'' of the allegations. `` Amnesty International's mention of the existence of political prisoners in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is unfounded,'' it said. It also said the government made a detailed check of cases mentioned by Amnesty and found the cases were properly described by Mexican police and judicial authorities as involving common crimes `` without the influence of any kind of political situation.'' The ministry said <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> `` distributes reports without checking the facts and without an opportune presentation to the government of our country.'' <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said it was in communication with the government by letter and visits by government representatives to the organization. Its annual report said at least 23 people adopted as `` prisoners of conscience'' by the organization remain in jail. Some of the prisoners have been sentenced for crimes such as robbery, assault and homicide the report said but it added `` it seems these charges were imposed for political motives, for legal, peaceful activities as campesino or community leaders.''
