<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friday was the last day on the air for radio station <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION>, for 62 years the flagship of the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> radio network that was home to <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Benny </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> conducted by <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Toscanini </PERSON>. Its spot at 660 on the AM dial, a clear-channel signal that could be picked up in as many as 35 states at night, is going to an all-sports station. <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> was descended from the station that was the first to broadcast a World Series, the first to run a commercial, the first with a coast-to-coast hookup and the first to broadcast a national political convention. At the end of the show, everyone in the studio counted down from 10, but the power was turned off before <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s distinctive three-gong chime could sound for the last time. The switch was thrown at 5:30 p.m. The end of an era came as a result of the $ 6 billion deal in 1985 in which <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> RCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regulation prevents a new owner from keeping both a TV and radio station in the same market, so <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> decided to sell its new radio properties and keep the more profitable <ORGANIZATION> WNBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> radio network went to Westwood One for $ 55 million, and five stations, including <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION>, were sold to <ORGANIZATION> Emmis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 121.5 million. GE has one station left, <ORGANIZATION> KNBR </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, which is for sale. <ORGANIZATION> Emmis </ORGANIZATION> decided to ditch <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION>'s call letters and format and move in its <ORGANIZATION> WFAN </ORGANIZATION>, a local all-sports station that held the less desirable frequency of 1050. The new station signed on from its studios in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> at 5:30 p.m., with the words, `` Sports radio 66 W-F-A-N.'' About 50 <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> employees, including its on-air personalities, have known since February they would be out of jobs, but none jumped ship ahead of time, said general manager <PERSON> Peg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> `` People sort of want to be here for the end,'' she said. `` No one's thrilled about it; no one even likes it. But it's kind of a piece of history, and people want to be here for it.'' <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> said goodbye with a 90-minute retrospective program Friday featuring clips from programs with <PERSON> Benny </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fibber </PERSON> <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Molly </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> also had such classic shows as `` Amos' n' <PERSON> Andy </PERSON>,'' `` Your Hit Parade'' and `` Information, Please.'' There were also the original soap operas, like `` Ma Perkins'' and `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Noble </PERSON>, Backstage Wife.'' The station, then owned by <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T, went on the air in April 1922 as W2XY. It became WBAY in July that year and was changed to <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION> the next month. RCA bought the station from <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T for $ 1 million in 1926 when it formed <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> to help sell the radios it was making, but it did n't change the call letters to <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> until 1946 The first radio commercial was broadcast on <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 28, 1922, when a real estate developer paid $ 100 for a 10-minute announcement to advertise apartments. `` Up to that point radio was for experimenters and people were still thinking of ways to make money with it,'' said <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> program director <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>, one of those losing a job. <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION>'s other firsts included the first World Series broadcast, <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> vs. Giants, in 1923; the first coast-to-coast hookup, in 1924, and the first broadcast of the national political conventions, in 1924. In 1925, it broadcast a presidential inaugural address _ <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON>'s _ for the first time.
