 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> came to <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s defense on Friday, portraying the embattled vice presidential candidate as a man who shares <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s conservative beliefs and should help carry on his policies. In a series of speeches designed to win support for Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his running mate among middle-class and blue-collar voters, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> mentioned <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> more than he usually does on campaign trips. He praised <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s performance in his face-off against the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential candidate, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` One thing's even clearer to me after watching the debate Wednesday night _ the <ORGANIZATION> Bush-Quayle </ORGANIZATION> ticket will continue the policies of peace and prosperity that have, as <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> said, made this great nation ` the envy of the world,''' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told a cheering group of several hundred business leaders. To a screaming, flag-waving crowd of 10,000 students and residents in nearby <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> earlier in the day, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said with a grin, `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economy is a Grand Prix racer, and the way to keep it on track is to give <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> a checkered flag in their race in November.'' Late Friday, the president spoke at a $ 1,000-per-plate <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> fund-raiser and attempted to counter the idea that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s performance had cost votes `` The other night ... the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> establishment was betting against him,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` But I tell you, the smart money was riding on a great senator, by the name of <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. He got my vote. How about yours?'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> then predicted that in November, `` the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people will be investing in a new option for the American engine _ I call it the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> turbocharger. And when that happens, all I can say is, Put the pedal to the metal and watch <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> go.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s references to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> came amid an apparent Republican damage-control effort to blunt criticism of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s performance in the <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, debate. Instant polls conducted after the event showed the public, by a wide margin, believed <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> had handily beaten <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> in the debate. The president said, `` The liberals are saying they want to help the American middle class. And what they're planning to do ... is to tax them and tax them and tax them some more. If you ask me, the liberals are selling the middle class short.'' He said the nation had enjoyed economic good times during his eight years in office and suggested that the economic hardship the state endured as the auto industry suffered might return under a Democratic administration. `` And you may have heard that I kind of like what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said about this election _ ` when you have to change horses in <LOCATION> midstream </LOCATION>, does n't it make sense to switch to one who's going the same way,''' he said. After <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ended his speech, a man claiming he had been the subject of government mind control experiments disrupted the event, making a long and rambling argument that he had been mistreated. <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents, apparently determining that he was not a p