<HEAD>Underground Coal Fire Is Extinguished</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NELSONVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An underground coal fire discovered by children when sticks they poked into the ground caught fire has been extinguished by firefighters with water and synthetic foam into holes bored into the earth. No houses in the southeast <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> city of 5,000 people were damaged by the fire, which had covered a 40-by-40-foot area, but it had threatened as many as 30 homes. `` We were lucky to get to it in its infancy,'' Fire Chief <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> said Friday. The burning material, waste coal believed to have come from an unmapped mine abandoned in the 1920s, was 4 feet deep. It was discovered Sept. 30. On Wednesday and Thursday, firefighters drilled holes about the size of fire extinguishers into the ground to determine the area of the fire, <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> said. Once isolated, additional holes were dug throughout the area and water was poured into them. `` That is a quenching effect. The quenching essentially would take away the heat,'' the chief said. After another dousing of water, firefighters capped the holes with a synthetic material, which <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> described as a type of firefighting foam used to fight oil fires by smothering them. `` What that essentially does is knock out the oxygen. That way we keep all the oxygen out of it,'' <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> said. Officials determined after additional core samples taken Friday that the fire died out. <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> said the fire entered a coal seam and could have burned indefinitely had it not been extinguished immediately.
