<HEAD>Italian Fashions Have a Relaxed Style for Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The curtain has come down on <ORGANIZATION> Milan </ORGANIZATION>'s fashion runways with audiences confident that spring-summer 1989 will be a good year for <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s designers. After the shock treatment of last year's miniskirts, intended to revive exports that slipped about 2 percent from 1986 to 1987, it appeared time to relax. For the moment, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> fashion seems to have the lead on creativity, riding in the wake of <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> LaCroix </PERSON>'s vivid imagination, but buyers still look to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> for well-tailored clothes. `` These collections are very saleable,'' said <PERSON> Elin </PERSON> <PERSON> Saltzman </PERSON>, fashion director at <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION>, of the five-day Italian ready-to-wear showings that ended Thursday. The look for next summer is soft and serene. Gone is the aggressiveness of a bold hemline, a hugged hip or a bulky padded shoulder. Instead the accent is on a rounded silhouette with small shoulders, tapered waistline and long loose hemlines. There is frequent use of rose and cream-colored shades. Pants, out during the miniskirt craze but reinstated in March as the dominant winter look, continued their popularity. Mainly they are ample and often cropped at the calf. Another favorite is the high-waisted sailor pant. Nautical themes pop up throughout the collections from the profuse use of navy blue and blue and white striping to sailor-suit collars on white blouses and jackets. The lore of the exotic influenced the collections with low-waisted sarong skirts and pants, bolero jackets, Chinese prints and Indian embroidery. <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Biagiotti </PERSON> brought 20 Chinese models to <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for her collection. Following in alphabetical order are glimpses of who offers what for spring and summer: <ORGANIZATION> Armani </ORGANIZATION> _ Soft daytime suits in silk tweeds and evening wear in diaphanous chiffon and embroidered silk. <PERSON> Basile </PERSON> _ Feminine blazers and long pants or skirts by day, strapless chiffon gowns by night. Byblos _ <LOCATION> Carioca </LOCATION> skirts, calypso pants and tropical wrap around skirts. Fendi _ A schoolgirl look in pleated linen carried into the night by demure touches such as lace collars and floral embroidery. <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> _ Nautical in an almost exclusive preference for navy blue or blue and white stripes. <PERSON> Genny </PERSON> _ Tightest and shortest look on the runway with toreador pants and short-skirted black suits. <PERSON> Gigli </PERSON> _ Waif-like with knotted hemlines and long sleeves. <ORGANIZATION> Krizia </ORGANIZATION> _ Sporty jackets and jumpers for daytime and <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>'s prettiest evening gown in tea rose silk organza <LOCATION> Missoni </LOCATION> _ Back to his artistry in Murano glass and <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Klimt </PERSON> designs for sumptuous knitwear. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> _ Leather patchworked or embroidered to look like fabric in bright citrus shades or muted tones. Versace _ High waists on pants and skirts with a preference for black and white, a night-look in transparent chiffon tops.
