<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Officials in a small town clashed with citizens demanding their ouster and a soldier guarding the officials shot and killed one of the demonstrators, an independent radio station reported Friday. Some Haitians said Thursday's confrontation in <LOCATION> Desdunes </LOCATION>, 150 miles north of the capital, was one of several indicating the military government is clamping down on the reform movement launched by a Sept. 17 soldiers' rebellion. In unrelated fighting about 50 miles south of <LOCATION> Desdunes </LOCATION>, two people were killed Friday in a feud between members of two families over land and hundreds of people fled their homes fearing a massacre, according to Radio Haiti-Inter. Radio Haiti-Inter said the fight in <LOCATION> Desdunes </LOCATION> began after groups representing youths, peasants and planters met to formulate demands for disarming members of the <ORGANIZATION> Tonton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macoutes </ORGANIZATION> and repressive government officials. The Tonton Macoutes were the private militia that supported the 29-year dictatorship of the <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> family. The demonstrators took to the streets intending to shut down government offices, the broadcast said. Before they got to the courthouse they were blocked by `` The Steamroller,'' a group of henchmen and city officials led by Mayor <PERSON> Anthenor </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercius </PERSON>, the radio said. The mayor's group, guarded by soldiers, threw rocks at the protesters, and four soldiers protecting the demonstrators withdrew to their barracks, the broadcast said. It said a soldier in the mayor's group, Sgt. <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valco </ORGANIZATION>, killed a youth identified as <ORGANIZATION> Evarol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racine </ORGANIZATION> and wounded another man in the foot. Four other demonstrators were injured by rocks, the radio said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Latortue </PERSON>, an economist who ran for the region's <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat in November's violently aborted national elections, said the town is a stronghold of the <ORGANIZATION> Tonton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macoutes </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Latortue </PERSON> noted that on Sunday, the government said it was temporarily suspending the search for <ORGANIZATION> Tonton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macoutes </ORGANIZATION>. On Wednesday, soldiers killed a squatter in the capital, and on Thursday they dispersed a demonstration in the town of <LOCATION> Port-de-Paix </LOCATION>, he said. The government believes `` the social potential of the soldiers' reform movement is too high, it must be reduced and checked,'' <PERSON> Latortue </PERSON> said The enlisted men of the Presidential Guard overthrew the military government of Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> in a bloodless coup on Sept. 17 and named Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> to replace him. The soldiers demanded an improvement in living conditions for themselves, the ouster of unpopular military and government officials, and a return to the 1987 Constitution, which <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> suspended. In the initial reaction to the coup, people across the country chased down, killed and burned several <LOCATION> Tonton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Macoutes </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Latortue </PERSON> said <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> has consolidated his power and promoted non-commissioned officers to bring them into line. `` Avril is successfully bringing off a vast seduction campaign on behalf of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> aid,'' <PERSON> Latortue </PERSON> said. `` But the fist in the velvet glove is iron.'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio-Metropole </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday that Haitian employees of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> petitioned for immediate resumption of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. Two-thirds of the $ 90 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid package was cut off last year when November's elections were canceled. Thugs supported by the army attacked and killed 34 people at the polls. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> took over after dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> fled to exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in February 1986. <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> ruled after the 1971 death of his father, <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>, who took over in 1957. Radio Haiti-Inter said its reporter in <LOCATION> Estere </LOCATION>, 100 miles north of <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>, said one person was was shot to death, another was killed by machete blows and `` many people'' were clubbed or stoned in fighting Friday in the fertile <LOCATION> Artibonite </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. It said the feud involves members of the Hatier and <PERSON> Bercourt </PERSON> families who have had violent disputes for years over land ownership. The report said that after a fatal shooting, <PERSON> Hatier </PERSON> property near <LOCATION> Estere </LOCATION> was invaded by members of the Desdunes-based <PERSON> Bercourt </PERSON> and in the fighting, hundreds of residents fled the area in panic. It said police made one arrest and called for reinforcements to help restore calm. In July 1987, more than 250 people were killed near the town of <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabel </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Artibonite </LOCATION> province in battles involving a dispute between an association of landless peasants and a coalition of landowners and sharecroppers.
