<HEAD>Four Killed In Gun Factory Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire at a rural gun factory Friday killed four people, destroyed the building and forced firefighters to retreat as bullets whizzed by them, authorities said. The bodies of four people were recovered from the rubble of the Buffalo Rock Shooters Supply, which makes ammunition and machine guns for police departments around the country, authorities said. `` It was a big ball of fire with a couple of explosions. There were a lot of bullets flying,'' said <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Dettore </PERSON>, fire chief of <PERSON> Naplate </PERSON>, a town about four miles east of the factory. <PERSON> Dettore </PERSON> said workers were believed to have been making bullets when the first explosion hit about 11:30 a.m. in the main building, which also housed the company's general offices and gun shop. The official cause was unknown, but fire investigators suspect a spark may have ignited gunpowder used to make bullets, he said. <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> is about 70 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` It started in the main bulding where they make ammunition and sell guns,'' <PERSON> Dettore </PERSON> said. `` A place like that with all that black powder _ just the dust, if you get a spark in there that's all it's going to take They had cases and cases and cases of all kinds of ammunition, all kinds of guns.'' The victims had not been positively identified Friday night and <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Coroner <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON> said through a spokesman that the process would n't be finished until Saturday. <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON>, the coroner's secretary, said a forensic dentist was summoned to help identify the bodies. When firefighters arrived at the company's complex, they began battling the blaze as bullets whizzed through the air, <PERSON> Dettore </PERSON> said. `` It's not as dangerous as if it was shot out of a gun itself,'' the fire chief said. `` It gets a little scary when you get a big explosion.'' But <PERSON> Dettore </PERSON> said that when he found out the buildings contained substantial amounts of gunpowder, he ordered the 40 firefighters to retreat about a half mile. They stayed away for about 45 minutes and resumed fighting the fire about 1 p.m., <PERSON> Dettore </PERSON> said. They had most of the fire put out in about an hour, though small fires still flared. More than 120 firefighters battled the blaze.
