 Opposition leaders said Friday that they want President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> out of office before 1990, despite his vow to complete his term after losing a referendum. Hundreds of thousands celebrated the `` no'' vote. Ten people were wounded, two seriously, when soldiers fired on celebrants in passing cars, a radio station reported. Six journalists in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> to cover the referendum also were slightly injured when they were caught between riot police and demonstrators Friday night near the national palace. Four of the injured required treatment at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clinic </LOCATION> for head wounds. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, a moderate Socialist prominent in the 16-party opposition alliance, said the president, who is also army commander, has `` too great an ambition for power'' and should heed the message this week by voters `` who said ` No more.''' Hundreds of thousands of Chileans swayed and sang along with some of the country's most popular music groups in a park Friday in an opposition celebration. No politicians spoke and the music was pointedly non-political, but people chanted on their own: `` <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON>, Get Out Pinochet!'' and `` He's Going to Fall!'' People bound for the park in buses and packed automobiles chanted anti-government slogans and waved anti-Pinochet banners. Police estimated the crowd at up to 350,000. A free presidential election is to be held late next year because of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s loss in the yes-or-no referendum Wednesday on whether he should remain in office until 1997. He can run in that election if he chooses. The winner takes office in March 1990 and <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said Thursday night he will not permit changes in the election schedule and he vowed not to leave office early. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> took power in a September 1973 coup that ousted Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>. While there was a peaceful gathering in the capital's biggest park on a warm hazy afternoon, there was violence elsewhere later. <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperativa </ORGANIZATION>, an independent news station, reported soldiers outside an army barracks near the park fired buckshot and pellets at people in passing cars who flashed the V sign for victory. It said two people were seriously wounded and eight were treated at <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> Central Emergency Hospital. A hospital spokesman told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> nine people were treated for gunshot wounds and a 10th was taken to a neurological hospital. Several hundred youths leaving the rally behind the national palace tried to stage a demonstration. Police, anticipating trouble, blocked the street off to traffic, then scattered the youths with water cannon and tear gas. The demonstrators regrouped, however. During the charge, riot police kicked and lashed with nightsticks at newsmen. `` We were crouched behind a fruit stand _ not in the way and trying to get out of the way,'' <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> photographer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> said. `` It happened so quick, nobody flashed -LRB- photographed -RRB- them. We did nothing to draw attention to us.'' Opposition leaders have requested talks with the government on amending the constitution and speeding <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s departure. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> said the administration might become more flexible later. `` You have to give the defeated a couple of days to recover from the shock,'' he said. `` Let's talk more seriously about it next week.'' He said the opposition should unify in its bid for an earlier election, declaring: `` If we join together with more force, I think the situation will change.'' Interior Minister <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said the government would negotiate with the opposition only `` if it was necessary.'' <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Plata </PERSON>, the labor minister, said: `` These people participated in the referendum and have to abide by the rules of the game.'' <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> spoke to reporters outside a federal prison where he visited a more radical Socialist, <PERSON> Clodomiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylmeda </PERSON>, who is serving a 541-day term on charges of promoting political violence through public anti-government statements. Whether <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> can resist opposition pressure is expected to depend on support from his army, and no splits in the ranks were evident Friday. Gen. <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibanez </PERSON>, governor of the southern <ORGANIZATION> Eighth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted Friday by <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Epoca </PERSON>, a moderate <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> daily, as saying: `` We have lost a battle, but not the war. This is an electoral defeat for the governent, but from the military point of view it's no more than a battle. He accused voters of `` ingratitude,'' the report said. The navy, air force and national police are generally seen as more willing to negotiate with the opposition but lack the army's size and political clout <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s 1980 constitution gives the military autonomy and an influential role in national policy under a democratic government.
