<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 10,0731</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct. 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mixed Reviews for Market `Circuit Breakers' Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If all goes as expected, the nation's stock markets will soon embark on an experiment they hope never gets put to the test. The plan, now awaiting approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, calls for `` circuit breakers'' that would halt all trading for set periods of time if stock prices fall by specified amounts on any given day. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> would stop trading for one hour if the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 250 points. After that, if the Dow fell 150 points more in the same session, trading would be halted for two hours. The system, developed by the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, would also provide that the prices of stock index futures traded on the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> would be effectively frozen for 30 minutes if they declined by an amount roughly equivalent to 100 Dow points. The proposal was made `` contingent on adoption by all domestic markets.'' <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the plan might hit a snag because of opposition from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the over-the-counter market. The <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION> does indeed regard the plan as `` a bad solution'' to the issues raised by the market crash last October, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardiman </PERSON>, the organization's president, said in an interview. But he indicated his group would go along with whatever the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> decides, and said he would be surprised if the commission did not approve the circuit-breaker plan in some form soon. The circuit breakers, along with a series of other measures proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>, are designed to supersede the `` collar'' adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> early this year. The collar closed the exchange's main computer trading facilities to orders from professionals engaged in multiple transactions known as index arbitrage whenever the Dow rose or fell 50 points in a day. Other trading, including `` manual'' index arbitrage, was not affected by the collar. In its brief existence, the collar has drawn mixed reviews. And the circuit breaker system has attracted divergent comments as well. To its proponents, it provides a system for everyone involved in the trading process to stop and evaluate the situation if a selling panic hits. Also, they say, it helps answer the call from the presidential commission headed by <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, now secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, for a recognition that activity in stocks and stock-index options and futures be recognized as `` one market.'' Of course, the hope is that the system will help restore investor confidence to the extent that the circuit breakers never actually have to be activated. On the other side of the debate, <PERSON> Hardiman </PERSON> says: `` Circuit breakers are likely to increase market volatility rather than curb it. The closer a market gets to a circuit breaker level, the more likely it is to reach it as sellers rush to execute orders under the wire.'' A similar contention, that the limit would tend to become a magnet, was made when the collar was adopted. Experience with the collar has neither proved nor refuted that point. <PERSON> Hardiman </PERSON> also cites academic studies that show markets as most volatile when a security is opening or reopening after a trading halt. Industry organizations `` should be striving to keep the markets open,'' he maintains. If the circuit breakers as proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> had been in effect for 50 years, they never would have been activated until last fall. So the statistical chances are not great that the system will be tested during the one-year `` pilot program'' the exchange is calling for. Presumably, the plan's workability would be demonstrated by a healthier performance by stock prices and increases in measures of investor confidence such as price-earnings ratios. But some Wall Streeters do not buy that idea. `` The proposed circuit breakers are no protection at all,'' says <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Legg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Stopping trading for an hour when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> industrials are down 250 points means you've done nothing until the market's plunged 12 percent. Thanks a lot.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon Oct 10</NOTE>
