<HEAD>Kenya's President Observes 10 Years of Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lower-case arap correct for middle name 1st graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 During 11 years as vice president to <PERSON> Jomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> says, his job was to `` sing the tune'' of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s first president. A decade after <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>'s death and <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>'s emergence from an understudy to the `` Mzee'' -LRB- Old Man -RRB- to the starring role in Kenyan politics, the schoolteacher-turned-president has taught all would-be challengers to dance to his drums. Through shrewd political maneuvering, the church-going, teetotaling <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>, a member of the minority <LOCATION> Kalengin </LOCATION> tribe, has amassed power that rivals even the lionized <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>'s. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> is by law a one-party state and <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> is boss of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Kenyan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, a body he says is supreme to the government. Parliament is essentially a rubber stamp to the president's wishes, and recent constitutional changes have brought the judiciary more under the executive's control <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>, too, ran <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> with a tight rein and tolerated no dissent. So pervasive was his rule that many doomsayers predicted <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> would be torn apart by tribal warfare after the death of <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>, who was a member of the predominant Kikuyu tribe. But when the <PERSON> Mzee </PERSON> died on Aug. 22, 1978, <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>, the third and longest-serving of <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>'s vice presidents, peacefully succeeded him. Within 90 days, as specified by the constitution, <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> called a presidential election. He won it unopposed and was sworn in as <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s second president Oct. 14, 1978, the date he observes as the beginning of his presidency. In the following months, government officials released details of what they said had been a plot during <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>'s waning days to kill <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> rather than allow the presidency to fall into the hands of a non-Kikuyu. Though there were no arrests, officials privately linked the plot to unidentified <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON> aides and relatives who months before had tried unsuccessfully to thwart the constitutional transfer of power to <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> retained many of <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>'s political allies, although some were his political enemies. It was only in September that he succeeded in ridding the party of the last vestiges of <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>'s power clique In a week of party elections _ beginning with grassroots balloting and ending with selection of national officers _ <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> retained the party presidency, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s supreme political job, but the eight officers under him changed, cementing <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>'s power base. During his 15 years of rule after independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON> would wave a flywisk, his symbol of office, and lead cheering crowds in <LOCATION> Kiswahili </LOCATION> chants of `` Harambee'' -LRB- Let's pull together -RRB-. <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>, saying he and the nation would be guided by the course <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON> had charted, adopted as his symbol of office and <PERSON> Poer </PERSON> a gold and ivory baton and proclaimed a new slogan: `` Nayo'' -LRB- FootstEp -RRB-. In his first days in office, <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> emptied the jails of political detainees, but began his own detentions after junior officers of the air force unsuccessfully tried to overthrow him on Aug. 1, 1982. Five people are now detained under a security law that allows the government to jail people indefinitely without trial. About 100 other people _ including journalists, lawyers, academics and civil servants _ have been jailed in the past 30 months after confessing links with several groups accused of plotting to overthrow <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>. The campaign against purported dissidents brought unaccustomed criticism of <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> from human rights groups and others who charged confessions were coerced and that civil liberties were being trampled. `` President <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> has presided over a steady deteroriation of the rule of law,'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Styron </PERSON>, chairwoman of the judge's panel of the <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Award </ORGANIZATION>, said in September when announcing that the Kenyan lawyer and former political detainee <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamau </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuria </PERSON> was the 1988 winner. `` <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> today is a land where only the animals are truly free,'' she said. <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> is popular with <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s masses and enjoys the reputaton with Western governments as a moderate. He has cordial ties with most of his African peers, but is cool to military rulers. He has made <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>'s best friend in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Western governments, in turn, hold <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> up to other African nations as an example, citing its robust capitalist economy and cooperation among the races. <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> remains a mecca for tourists. It's able to feed itself, a rarity in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and is one of the few countries in the region not troubled with civil war. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s economy is one of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s success stories, but has started to stagger under the burden of the world's fastest-growning population _ a nearly 4 percent pace that is expected to double the 22 million population by the beginning of the century. The population includes 300,000 non-blacks, most of them `` Asians,'' the collective name for people from the Indian subcontinent. There are about 60,000 `` Europeans,'' the name Africans assign to all whites. On the eve of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s independence in 1963 and despite his armed Mau-Mau revolt in 1952-56 against British rule, <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON> appealed to whites and other non-Africans to stay put and to help build black-led <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. Most did and many continue to prosper under <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>. Minorities, especially the Asians, still control a disproportionate amount of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s economy _ from groceries and clothing stores to major factories. But whites have no political clout. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Leakey </PERSON>, son of anthropologists <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Leakey </PERSON>, is the only non-black member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and serves as an assistant minister of tourism and wildlife. His brother, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, is director of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s museums. <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>, 64 years old and divorced, is a private person. He does not give interviews. Most of his comments are gleaned from his frequent appearances at public rallies where he staunchly defends <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and his government. `` We are a sovereign state and can stand on our feet,'' he said recently in at attack on foreign critics. `` We are not under anyone's feet.'' The Kenyan press, one of the most sophisticated in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, is assailed by a chorus of protests, often led by <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>, when it publishes stories that are not to the government's liking. A church-run magazine, Beyond, was banned earlier this year after publishing an article alleging fraud during primary elections. Nowadays, clergymen and the Law Society of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> are the only public critics of government and even their protests are presented so as not to offend or even mention the head of state. `` We are conscious of a certain inadequacy of dialogue in the country,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> said in a letter to <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> in November 1986. `` At present, discussion is precluded by allegation of powerful party officials that any questioning of the system is tantamout to disloyalty,'' the bishops added. `` Already the party is assuming a totalitarian role.''
</TEXT>
