<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Calls For FAA Overhaul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> should be freed of bureaucratic red tape and made an independent government corporation, similar to <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of Transportation <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said regulation of aviation safety should remain in the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. But he told the <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> needs independence to `` do a much better job of modernizing air traffic control and keeping pace with growth.'' The <ORGANIZATION> AOPA </ORGANIZATION> represents private aircraft owners and pilots. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> is a unique federal agency because it combines three distinct and somewhat contradictory missions,'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said. He said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> is charged with establishing and enforcing aviation safety regulations, providing air traffic control service and encouraging development of civil aeronautics and air commerce. <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said he wanted to retain control of aircraft safety because `` aviation will do much better in the annual budget battles with the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with a cabinet secretary as its spokesman.'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> also called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to act on a `` tort liability crisis in general aviation manufacturing'' that has resulted in insurance costs rising fivefold since 1981, while sales have dropped from 17,000 planes in 1979 to 1,500 in 1986. `` While <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> procrastinates on the resolution of this urgent issue, general aviation manufacturers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are poised to invade <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets,'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> also said: _ He was concerned by alcohol and drug abuse among pilots, noting that indictments were handed down in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, last week `` against some two dozen pilots for failing to disclose convictions for drug and alcohol related offenses on the Airman Medical Certificates they provided to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. _ Nationally, there is `` a dire need for airport expansion and improvement A major airport has not been constructed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> opened in the mid-70s,'' although he noted that <LOCATION> Adams </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, residents voted in May to permit <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> to annex land for a new hub airport.
