<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Unable To Sustain Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have wilted following a technical rally that failed to shake off market concerns about <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s threats to overproduce crude. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> rose 6 cents to settle at $ 12.66 a barrel on Thursday, but other contract months settled as much as 15 cents lower. The near-term contract had been up as much as 30 cents during the session. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose .06 cent to settle at 39.50 cents a gallon, while home heating oil slipped 0.52 cent to 37.24 cents a gallon. Other contract months finished lower. Traders said a technical rally gripped the market, pushing prices higher by midday, but broke down shortly thereafter on a dearth of encouraging news. `` The market still looks sick,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He said participants were continuing to focus on <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s production levels. Earlier this week <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the world's largest oil exporter, threatened not to restrain its own production if other members of the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> cartel continued to pump beyond their quotas. `` That's old news, but it's still the focus of the market, and there's a feeling that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has not yet achieved its goals and will continue to pressure prices,'' <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> said. The Saudis have indicated they want to punish other members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries for overproducing and driving down the price of oil. Traders also remained concerned about a report that surfaced Wednesday that said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> chartered a number of tankers to transport a substantial amount of oil out of the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, presumably from <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. The market interpreted the report as further `` confirmation that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has increased production,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
