<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Improve From August, But Sluggish Trend Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 September reports from the nation's largest general retailers have given no indication that the companies' 19-month-old sales slump will end soon, but industry analysts say storeowners have taken steps to protect their profits. `` Sales for the early part of the month through mid-month recorded a nice uptick,'' but retailers were unable to sustain that improvement the rest of September, <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said after reviewing Thursday's reports Retailers hoped September would end the sluggish sales trend that began a year and a half ago, but last month's numbers `` were n't quite as good as expected,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sack </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It does n't look like the turnaround that people expected will be here,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sack </PERSON> said, predicting retailers would see only modest sales increases for the rest of 1988. But retailers have kept inventories lean and pared expenses, steps that should help their third-quarter earnings, said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Feiner </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Ms. <PERSON> Sack </PERSON> agreed, saying, `` We're not going to see the kind of pressure on their margins,'' as in recent quarters `` I think it's safe to say the worst is over for retailers,'' she said. The analysts said softness in retail sales was not necessarily a sign of weakness in consumer spending, which is watched closely as an economic indicator because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product. `` Consumers are spending at a very high rate _ they've just been moving to other areas like durables,'' said <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc.. Ms. <PERSON> Sack </PERSON> noted consumers also have been spending more for services _ such as utilities and medical care _ leaving them less money for general merchandise and Apparel sales, which have been in a year-long slump of their own, improved slightly last month, but analysts still described them as weak. Several retailers recorded sales increases of 3 percent or less _ meaning they continued to lose ground to inflation, which has run at an annual rate of 4.6 percent so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest retailer, said its overall sales rose 6.6 percent in September and 5.7 percent for the first 35 weeks of the fiscal year. Sales from <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> stores open at least a year _ known in the trade as same-store or comparable sales _ were up 1.6 percent last month and 2 percent for the year to date. Retailers and industry analysts believe same-store sales are a more accurate yardstick of a company's performance than figures which include sales from new stores. But not all retailers report both overall and same-store results. K mart <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 7.1 percent last month and 5.6 percent for the cumulative 35-week period. Same-store sales were up 3 percent for September and 2 percent for the year to date. <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales were up 25 percent overall last month, while climbing 30 percent so far this year. Same-store sales, meanwhile, were up 10 percent in September and 11 percent for the year to date. <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 1.3 percent in September, and 1.7 percent for the year to date <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>'s same-store sales were up 0.7 percent for the month and 0.6 percent so far this year <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 15.1 percent last month, and 16.9 percent for the year to date. Same-store sales picked up 2.9 percent in September and 1.7 percent so far this year. May <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 21 percent in September while picking up 14.6 percent so far this year. Same-store sales were up 3 percent for the month and 1.6 percent for the year to date. F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its September sales rose 13.7 percent, while year-to-date sales rose 12.2 percent. Same-store sales rose 7.2 percent for the month and 5.9 percent for the first 35 weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales were up 3.5 percent in September and 3.1 percent so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest specialty apparel retailer, said its overall sales rose 11 percent last month and 6 percent for the year to date. Limited's same-store sales were up 7 percent in September _ an improvement over the company's performance in recent months _ while falling 1 percent over the cumulative 35-week period. Apparel sales began slumping in August 1987, when many women turned away from shorter skirts and fashions they considered boring. The results reported Thursday were from general merchandise and apparel retailers. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by the federal government, they do not include sales at auto dealers, supermarkets or restaurants.
