<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The European Economic Community will not oppose <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s request for a special international trade panel to resolve their dispute over the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> anti-dumping policy, an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman said Friday. Speaking on the condition of anonymity, the spokeswoman said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> was confident its policy conformed with international trade rules. `` We are utterly serene'' about the formation of the panel, said the official. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has contended that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s imposition of anti-dumping duties on locally-assembled Japanese electronic typewriters and other products violates international trade rules. Specifically, the Japanese government believes that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is violating a rule of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade that requires locally based foreign manufacturers to be treated in the same manner as their domestic counterparts. A decision to form the panel likely will be made at a meeting on Oct. 19 of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> council, the international trade body, the spokeswoman said. Earlier this week, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> rejected a complaint by a number of Japanese companies that the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> used faulty accounting methods in anti-dumping cases.
