<SECOND>PM-Soviet Suit,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Dept. Attorney Says US-Soviet Relations Will Suffer Under
Suit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney, siding with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, told a federal appeals court that U.S.-Soviet relations will suffer unless an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman's unusual lawsuit is dismissed <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Letter </PERSON> said Thursday that the government takes no position on whether <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> is right or wrong in his contention that the Soviets libeled him. But he joined an attorney for the Soviets in arguing that the case should not be tried in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, businessman, sued the Soviets after they revoked his license to do business in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, where he had been selling medical equipment for 14 years. He was expelled and branded a spy in an article in the official Soviet newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>. His attorney, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON>, told a panel of the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in the one-day hearing that <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> deserves a trial. However, Letter argued: `` We have been working very closely with the Soviets and we have made wonderful progress. It's important that this progress not be set back. `` It is our position that under the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act, you can not sue a foreign entity for libel,'' Letter said. `` And even if you can, you ca n't do it on the facts of this case.'' <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> ridiculed Letter's contention that the fate of U.S.-Soviet relations depends on Gregorian. `` I personally think they have bigger people to fry than my client,'' he told the court. Reached by telephone, <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> expressed amazement at the statements about his role in international affairs. `` If being fair to me affects our relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, then we do n't have any relations,'' he said. `` The question is why have they -LRB- the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government -RRB- turned against me? I'm really too small a guy ... We're talking about two superpowers. This is infantile, sophomoric and unfair.'' One of the appellate judges, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinhardt </PERSON>, bristled at the mention of foreign relations, saying, `` Is n't that something we're supposed to ignore _ the political considerations _ in reaching our decision? <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mage </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> attorney representing the Soviets, insisted that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts do not have jurisdiction because the incidents in question did not occur in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He also said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is immune from a lawsuit as a foreign sovereign. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> argued that the Soviets libeled <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> in connection with a commercial enterprise and that such an action is exempt from the immunities act. <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>'s problems date back to 1984 when the Soviets said he could no longer sell medical equipment such as kidney dialysis and heart-lung machines. The Soviet newspaper then printed a story denouncing <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON> as a `` duplicitous negotiator,'' accusing him of bribery and smuggling and intimating that he was a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spy. <PERSON> Gregorian </PERSON>, adamant about his innocence, sued for libel and demanded payment for medical equipment still in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Soviets dispute his contention that he still has equipment there. The Soviet defendants ignored the suit until 1985, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> entered a default judgment against them, awarding Gregorian total damages of $ 413,000. Of that amount, $ 250,000 was for libel. The Soviets refused to pay. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> said he would seize Soviet assets and even took custody of a typewriter at an <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> correspondent's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> home as partial payment. The Soviets and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> went to court and asserted immunity from suit under the immunities act. Last year <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> reversed his own libel judgment, ruling that he did not have jurisdiction because of immunity considerations. But he let stand his ruling the Soviets should pay for the medical supplies. <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> appealed the libel ruling to the 9th Circuit. The Soviets appealed the contractual award as well as disputing the libel claim.
