<SECOND>BC-China-Investment,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Government to Clamp Down on Capital Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese officials have announced tough new measures to halt construction projects targeted in an upcoming nationwide crackdown on what the government considers excessive capital investment, which officials blame for high inflation. After Dec. 1, authorities will withhold bank loans, energy and building supplies and construction licenses from targeted projects to force them to close down, the official <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. The newspaper quoted senior official <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangjian </PERSON>, newly appointed by Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> to spearhead efforts to curb capital construction. He said projects slated for cancellation include those that rely on imported or scarce domestic raw materials, are underfinanced, will produce high-energy-consuming goods or goods that are already made in excess. Aside from a handful of projects already approved by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, construction will be halted on all office buildings, auditoriums and hotels begun this year. No new building will be allowed for two to three years, he said. According to a <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> report, <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> said projects which use imported technology and foreign funding are expected to escape cutting. Capital investment has grown at a rate of 18.8 percent over the past three years, far outstripping the 16.4 percent rate of increase in national income during the same period. The too-rapid rate of investment has helped fuel an inflation rate currently about 20 percent. <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> said blind emphasis on short-term profits in enterprises as well as the failure of local banks to abide by state loan quotas and policies were responsible for `` investment inflation.'' The Central Committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> launched an attack on inflation and confusion in the economy in its plenary session last week, criticizing party members and local officials for lax discipline in carrying out its economic policies. The central government has led repeated drives with little success against excessive capital investment, including a partial halt on hotel and theater construction earlier this year. Leaders intend the current campaign to be all-inclusive in scope, subjecting all capital investment nationwide to close scrutiny.
</TEXT>
