<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 8-9</NOTE>
<HEAD>Corn, Hog Markets Keep Watchful Eye On Aflatoxin Spread</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers across the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> are examining their corn while traders keep a watchful eye on the market as the discovery of a cancer-causing toxic mold _ a by-product of this summer's drought _ threatens to curb an already reduced crop. Early indications are that aflatoxin, though found already in several states, will not pose a serious problem, experts say. But concerns that the progressing harvest will reveal the mold is widespread have lent support to corn prices at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, analysts say. And aflatoxin is in the back of the minds of traders at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where prices of hogs _ a major corn consumer and especially vulnerable to the toxin _ would feel the effects of an outbreak. `` One thought is that it's going to reduce the corn supply,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, a livestock analyst and president of <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` The other concern is that if the contamination becomes too widespread it will hurt our exports _ countries would not want to buy'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn out of fear of contamination. `` So it could have a bullish or bearish impact,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. But with only about one-third of the nation's corn crop in the bin, it's too soon to tell, he said. The toxin is a metabolic by-product of the fungus Aspergillus flavus, which primarily affects corn and peanut crops, said <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON>, a plant pathologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>. The fungus appears on corn kernels in hot, dry weather and thrives in conditions like this past summer's drought, followed by the wet fall. Ordinarily, the fungus can only be detected through a series of tests. But on a severely affected ear of corn, it shows up as an olive-green colored mold, visible to the naked eye, he said. After tainted corn is harvested, the fungus will spread in storage unless the crop is kept cool and dry, <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. Neither heat treatment nor fungicides destroy the toxin. Animals generally begin showing symptoms such as loss of appetite and weight if fed corn tainted with about 200 to 300 parts per billion for a period of two months or more, <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. In extremely large doses, the toxin can cause liver cancer in humans. But it is `` highly unlikely'' that humans will be affected by the outbreak, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>, an animal sciences professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>. This year _ like the last aflatoxin outbreak in 1983, another drought year _ the toxin has been discovered in corn crops throughout the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. A statewide survey in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> of 327 corn samples has found 35.8 percent contained toxin levels of above 20 parts per billion, the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> said. Under <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> guidelines, corn destined for humans or dairy cattle must contain less than 20 parts per billion of the toxin. Corn for breeding cattle or swine must contain below 100 parts per billion. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> this past week revised its standards for corn shipped interstate, allowing up to 100 parts per billion if the feed is given only to mature animals. The Board of Trade recently announced that `` no corn could be delivered on our contracts that contained more than the 20 parts-per-billion limit from the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> guidelines,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Prout </PERSON>. Despite the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> revision, `` Our limit stays the same, to assure the users of our markets of the quality of the grain being traded,'' <PERSON> Prout </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> officials estimate that 10 percent to 14 percent of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> corn contains some amounts of the toxin. Milk containing unacceptable levels of aflatoxin has been traced to several <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> dairies. The toxin has appeared in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, and testing is being done in those states as well as in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. `` If we find out that a lot of the corn is affected and is toxic ... it will affect our costs of production down the road,'' said livestock analyst <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We're not feeding a lot of the new crop corn yet, we're still feeding a lot of the old crop corn. But if it really cuts into the availabilty of corn supplies next year ... it could stimulate some liquidation of hogs,'' <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said. The near-term effect would likely be a decline in hog futures prices, but the long-term impact of a diminished corn supply would be bullish. `` Tight corn supplies will eventually lead to tighter meat supplies, you can bet your bottom dollar,'' <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said. Since the 1983 drought, rapid screening tests have been devised that can detect the toxin in minutes, <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. At grain elevators, inspectors first put corn samples under an ultra-violet light. If kernels glow, the fungus is present, and a rapid antibody-antigen test is then performed to determine presence and amount of toxin. `` The elevators tell me they're turning away about 5 to 10 percent average corn for having more than 20 parts per billion,'' <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. `` If I were a farmer,'' he said, `` I would be sampling my grain, purchasing a rapid-screening test kit ... I would screen my grain and I would also be sure that I was storing my grain at a low-moisture level'' at lower than 70 degrees. `` I would definitely be concerned,'' <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said, `` but not be overly concerned. It's a management problem that can be dealt with.''
</TEXT>
