<HEAD>WNBC Signs Off After 62 Years On The Air</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to DELETE incorrect reference to election
returns; SUBS 11th graf, `WEAF had ...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICH MENDELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s radio flagship for 62 years and once home to <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Benny </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> conducted by <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Toscanini </PERSON>, goes off the air today as a result of a corporate takeover. The new owner is changing the talk and music station, a clear-channel spot on the dial at 660 that can be heard in 35 states at night, to an all-sports format. The station's forerunner was a pioneer with a string of firsts including such things as the first broadcast of a World Series and the first broadcast of the national political conventions. It also had the first broadcast commercial. <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION>'s signoff, announced Feb. 18, is the result of a $ 6 billion deal in 1985 in which <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> RCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regulation prevents a new owner from keeping both a television and a radio station in the same market. <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> decided to sell its new radio properties and keep the more profitable <ORGANIZATION> WNBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. GE sold the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> radio network to Westwood One for $ 55 million and sold five stations to <ORGANIZATION> Emmis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 121.5 million. One station is still up for sale, <ORGANIZATION> KNBR </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> signs off at 5:30 p.m. today and turns into <ORGANIZATION> WFAN </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Emmis </ORGANIZATION>' sports format station, previously heard at 1050 on the dial <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION>'s frequency, 660, is more desirable from an engineering standpoint The change means about 50 <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> employees are out of jobs. The station went on the air in April 1922 as W2XY, then owned by <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T. It became <ORGANIZATION> WBAY </ORGANIZATION> in July that year and changed to <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION> in August. RCA bought the station from <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T for $ 1 million in 1926 when it formed <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> to help sell the radios it was building. But the call letters were n't changed to <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> until 1946. `` The format has changed, the personalities have changed, the call letters have changed, change is inevitable,'' said <ORGANIZATION> WNBC </ORGANIZATION> program director <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>, one of those losing a job. <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION> had the first World Series broadcast, <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> vs. Giants, in 1923; the first coast-to-coast hookup in 1924; and the first broadcast of the national political conventions in 1924. In 1925, it broadcast a presidential inaugural address _ by <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON> _ for the first time. The first radio commercial was aired on <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 28, 1922, when a real estate developer from across the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> paid $ 100 for a 10-minute announcement to advertise apartments. `` Up to that point radio was for experimenters and people were still thinking of ways to make money with it,'' <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> said.
