 imformation. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> already has given conditional approval for an Irving-Bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> merger. Under its revised bid, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 4.9 percent of <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, would pay $ 15 in cash and 1.675 shares of its own stock for each of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s common shares outstanding. It also included warrants valued at $ 5 toward the purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> stock. The entire deal was worth about $ 78.42 a share, or about $ 1.48 billion, according to <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> figures. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> stock was trading at $ 74.75 a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Friday afternoon, up $ 1.12 -LCB- from late Thursday. All present directors of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> would be invited to join <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors under the proposed plan, and all key personnel decisions would be made by a committee of directors made up of three directors of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and two current <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> directors. When <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> first made its bid on Sept. 25, 1987, it had the distinction of being the first-ever hostile takeover fight between two big American banks. It then became the lengthiest such battle among major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations.
