<FIRST>r f AM-WashingtonApples     10-07 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Washington Apples,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growers Of Largest Apple Crop Optimistic</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON> is busy dodging swarms of forklifts around Snokist Growers' apple warehouses. The company president is trying to stay out of the way of 1,400 employees who clean, sort, pack and ship up to 1 million apples per day as the nation's largest apple crop moves into peak harvest. `` The receiving crews are working from 6 in the morning to 9 at night,'' <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON> said this week. `` We had 50,000 cartons packed last week.'' The forklifts are moving 700-pound bins of Red Delicious apples from trucks to sorting lines, or stacking them 11 high in refrigerated warehouses. And so it will go at 300 warehouses across central <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the next month as crews move 5.7 billion apples, handpicked by over 40,000 farmworkers, from a crop the industry hopes is a major improvement over 1987. Plagued by a record production, poor quality, weather damage, falling prices, and a <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> boycott, the 1987 apple crop was a major disaster for the state's 4,500 growers. Although the 68 million boxes of supermarket apples were 13 million above the previous state record, prices remained below the cost of production nearly the entire year. As a result, the $ 312.4 million growers received for apples was $ 177 million less than the year before. Things were so bad that Snokist, a cooperative with 380 member growers, failed to pay a dividend for only the second time in its 80-year history, <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON> said. The first time was in 1985 when frost wiped out 60 percent of the crop. This year's harvest is projected at only 57.2 million boxes, and quality is looking much better, growers say. `` This crop is a vintage crop,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, an industry trade group. `` It's remarkably good in color, size and inner quality.'' `` There is awfully high confidence this year,'' he said. Part of that optimism is based on national estimates of a crop of just 111 million boxes, 22 million boxes less than last year. That should keep prices up for apples, which trail only potatoes and lettuce in national produce sales. Early market prices of $ 14 to $ 16 per 42-pound box are well above the $ 9.50 per box growers need to break even. Last year, prices dropped as low as $ 5 per box. Although 35 states grow apples commercially, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> produces about half the nation's supermarket apples each year, and accounts for over 80 percent of apple exports. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> ranked second last year with 9.2 million boxes, followed by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with 9 million and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with 5.4 million boxes, the commission said. Exports were one of the few bright spots for the 1987 crop, setting a record despite the spring boycott by the EEC. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> growers blamed the boycott on the desire of the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> governments to protect their local growers from competition. The boycott has been lifted now. This year the industry is taking steps to ensure that consumers will get a crisper apple. For the first time, the industry has instituted a firmness standard that is designed to ensure that top grade apples stay crisp at least two weeks after they are shipped to supermarkets. Apples too soft to meet that requirement will be diverted to juice and applesauce processors. St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said the firmness standard, adopted this summer by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, can not guarantee proper handling by supermarkets, but is designed to ensure a better shelf life for the fruit. `` We lose control once we slam the door on the trucks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
