<SECOND>AM-Ego Trio, Bjt,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Queens and With King-Sized Egos, Trio Tries To Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They all hail from <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, and their egos are king-sized. Corporate raider <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, airline cost-slasher <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and glitzy real estate mogul <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> speak the language of the working-class <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> borough. They have made millions from their brash mega-deals. They live in luxury. Now each is keenly interested in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. The similarities are startling, but their unyielding tycoon styles raise the question of whether this ego trio ultimately can agree on a way to divvy up financially troubled Eastern, part of <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is believed to be looking to sell parts or all of Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has been fraught with labor conflict and staggering losses before and since he took over `` The question is whether there's a -LRB- negotiating -RRB- table big enough to get all three around,'' chuckled one Wall Street investment banker who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` It's very difficult to do any three-party deal, and when you have the likes of those three, it increases the degree of difficulty exponentially.'' <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who heads <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has met with <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> in the past to discuss the possibility of buying some Eastern assets. But he re-emerged this week, reportedly interested in acquiring all of Eastern except for its lucrative shuttle service. Enter <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, hotel and casino fame. He has his eye on the shuttle, which serves <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Despite the trading floor jokes, one Wall Street source noted that `` what you've got is three very sharp deal people, and there's a feeling they can probably come up with something very creative if they want to achieve the end result. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has retained the quick reflexes of his trader days. In typical raider fashion, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> buys into companies whose assets are worth more than their stock price, and then makes money selling the companies later _ whole or in pieces _ unless the companies offer to buy him out at a premium. His target list ranges from <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The only deterrent, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has said, is a company's stock price, a most telling `` report card.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> graduate and medical school dropout, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> resides in a verdant <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> suburb and has designed the gardens that skirt his mansion. But he is said to be more intensely interested in business than in indulging in the pleasures of wealth. Posing beside him in a photograph that appeared in Business Week magazine recently was a majestic German shepherd. But his interest in animals does n't stop there. Within his business empire are partnerships that bear the names <ORGANIZATION> Gnu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Wolf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Stork </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> man. His parents emigrated from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and ran a hairdressing salon in midtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, but their business, he once said, was hit hard by the advent of the do-it-at-home permanent wave. His goal has been to run businesses that are as lean as his distance-runner's frame. He shocked the industry in 1983 by filing to reorganize <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> under federal bankruptcy laws, firing all 12,000 employees in the process. He hired back only 4,000 at tremendous wage cuts. Often projecting a cold, tough-guy persona, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> threatened several times to have beefy security guards eject shareholders from the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> annual meeting in June because they continued their questioning after he had asked them to refrain. Beaming proudly this week when <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> announced a $ 50 million deal with <ORGANIZATION> Scandinavian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> was his neatly coiffed mother, who often attends his business functions. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, a product of military school and the <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, followed in his father's footsteps when he embarked upon a career as a developer. But he made his bailiwick <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, rather than the less tony outer boroughs. Success came before he was even 30, and <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> was eager to accumulate the riches his money could provide. He seems driven to have his name emblazoned on high-profile properties like skyscrapers, million-dollar condos, casinos and helicopters. In the 1970s he offered to build a $ 170 million convention center for the city of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> if his father's name could appear on it. The city declined. Among his recent purchases is the Plaza Hotel, a French Renaissance landmark adjacent to Central Park, which he purchased for about $ 400 million. The 808-room hotel is being run by his Czech-born wife, <PERSON> Ivana </PERSON>, for `` $ 1 a year and all the dresses she can buy.'' Under her tutelage, employees have been instructed to regularly stamp the sand in the hotel's ashtrays with the Plaza logo.
</TEXT>
