<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct 8-9</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bond Market Cheered by September Employment Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First Fridays are proving to be full of mostly pleasant surprises for the bond market. But some analysts see turbulence ahead. For the past two months, the first Friday has meant reassurance for bondholders worried that the economy may be growing so fast that inflation will accelerate and take a heavy toll on the value of their fixed-income securities. The first Friday of each month is when the government reports on the employment situation in the previous month, providing the most current official glimpse of the state of the economy. The reports for August and September have indicated to many analysts that the economy is growing at a moderate yet still healthy pace. More important, each of the reports was viewed as reducing chances that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would feel compelled to encourage higher interest rates. This past Friday, the government reported that the September unemployment rate slipped to 5.4 percent from 5.6 percent the previous month. Most bond traders focused on payroll employment growth, though, and the September increase of 255,000 jobs fell 45,000 short of expectations. The reaction was immediate. Prices jumped and trading volume swelled after slowing to a trickle in the past few days in anticipation of the report. By midafternoon, the price of the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond was up more than $ 15 for every $ 1,000 in face value and its yield was at 8.80 percent, its lowest level since mid-April. The rally was not quite as strong as the one that followed the release of the August unemployment figures, which saw the unemployment rate rise to 5.6 percent from 5.4 percent in July and payroll growth of 219,000. Bonds staged one of their biggest advances of the year that day, with some 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues rising more than $ 25 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Some analysts said the latest report confirmed the conclusion suggested by the unemployment report a month ago that the economy was moderating. `` It belied the notion that the August figures were an aberration,'' said <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, fixed-income research director for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It appears they were the beginning of a new moderate growth trend for the economy.'' But other analysts said economy continues to grow at a fairly strong pace and warned that higher interest rates may lie ahead. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Santow </PERSON>, managing director for <ORGANIZATION> Griggs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial consulting firm, said, `` The market was so fearful of huge increases that the number was greeted with a sigh of relief.'' He said the market's sharp rise Friday may also have reflected a delayed response to sharp declines in oil prices earlier in the week. Crude oil prices plunged below $ 13 a barrel to two-year lows at midweek, a plus for the inflation outlook, but the bond market barely moved as traders refused to budge before the unemployment report. On the other hand, some economists said the market may have ignored in its euphoria the wage data released with the unemployment report. It said, for instance, that real hourly earnings dropped 1.3 percent during the month while average hourly wages rose 0.5 percentage point. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of money market research for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the wage measurements `` provide a modest hint that there could be some pickup in wage inflation.'' Can the bond market extend Friday's advance? <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. Wood, money market economist for <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, noted that the big rally following the August unemployment report lasted only a day. `` It would n't surprise me to see the same kind of reaction this go around,'' he said, noting that the market runs into some important producer price and trade balance reports due to be released in the coming week.
</TEXT>
