<TEXT>
 The dollar closed narrowly lower Friday after it skidded and then regained some ground in response to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s release of September unemployment figures. Gold prices were little changed. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid of $ 403.30 for a troy ounce of gold, down 20 cents from late Thursday's $ 403.50. Analysts said the dollar fell after the government report, which included news that the nation's non-farm payroll grew by 255,000 jobs last month. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the unemployment rate fell 0.2 percent to 5.4 percent. Foreign exchange traders had expected a payroll increase of about 300,000, so the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s numbers came as a disappointment. Investors interpreted the payroll figures as a sign of weakness in the economy. But after further consideration, they `` realized the economy is growing steadily,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Frick </PERSON>, foreign exchange economist at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Switzerland </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In addition, dollar traders seeing the stock and bond markets improve on the unemployment data were heartened by the demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investments, said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Holzer </PERSON>, chief dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION