<FIRST>r f AM-HarborCleanup     10-07 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Harbor Cleanup,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outboard Marine Agrees to Pay Clean-up Costs, Ending Decade of
Litigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An outboard-motor manufacturer has agreed to finance a $ 20 million cleanup of PCBs in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, effectively ending years of bitter haggling over the Superfund site, state and federal officials announced Friday. Under a consent decree signed by <ORGANIZATION> Outboard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and federal and state officials, thousands of pounds of toxic polychlorinated biphenyls will be removed, treated and safely stored, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> said. `` This is a major environmental victory,'' <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> said, noting that no taxpayer dollars will be used in the clean-up. `` I think it's a sensational day.'' <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, an important <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> port at <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION>, 25 miles north of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, has been listed on the federal Superfund list of environmental hazards and at one time was considered Illinois' worst pollution problem. Public health officials have advised against eating fish from the harbor. PCBs have been shown to cause tumors in laboratory animals and are suspected to cause cancer in humans. `` We obviously believe that it's time to get this matter resolved,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Laurin </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> in a telephone interview from <ORGANIZATION> OMC </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION> headquarters. While acknowledging it is `` hard to be happy over spending $ 20 million in company assets,'' he said the decree `` is the best settlement possible.'' Contamination of the harbor began in 1961, when hydraulic fluid containing PCBs leaked from the hydraulic systems at the company's <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION> plant into waste waters, which were dumped into <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and onto Outboard Marine property The case became entangled in the legal system as company officials first argued PCBs posed no threat to humans, then barred from their facilities federal environmental officials seeking to determine how bad the pollution was, said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Perrecone </PERSON>. After 1986 changes in federal Superfund law allowed the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> such access, the company agreed to negotiate with state and federal authorities, <PERSON> Perrecone </PERSON> said. Under terms of Friday's consent decree, <ORGANIZATION> Outboard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> will begin cleaning up the PCBs next spring and should complete the task by 1992. The company will remove and treat contaminated material from both the harbor and its property. `` The agreement called for us to remove and treat sediments and soils that have the highest levels of contamination and encapsulate the remaining low-level soils and sediments in three areas,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. Outboard Marine is a $ 1.3 billion manufacturer of recreational marine products and other recreational materials.
</TEXT>
