<SECOND>AM-Cola-Price Fixing,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Reconsider Price-Fixing Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON>, who was told by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> he illegally sentenced a <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> bottling company to prison for price fixing, refused Friday to reconsider his sentence. In a six-page opinion, <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said he derived his sentence against <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` from the basic principle that, to the extent possible, the law treats all persons _ whether natural or corporate _ equally. `` Any other treatment would belie that basic principle and create a special class of persons which this Court is unwilling to foster,'' he wrote. In a Sept. 30 letter, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asked <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> to reconsider his novel sentence because prosecutors would be unable to defend the sentence on appeal. Last month, <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Allegheny </PERSON> to three years in prison and fined the company $ 1 million for fixing its soft drink prices in collusion with <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The scheme cost customers in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> more than $ 10 million. <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> warned attorneys and executives of the <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> bottler that the corporation was treated as an individual under the law, and he would not hesitate to have federal marshals shut down the plant. He then suspended the sentence and $ 50,000 of the fine on the condition that the company provide four high-ranking executives to perform one year each of full-time, free community service in each of the three cities victimized. <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said a $ 1 million fine, the maximum penalty for antitrust violations, was no deterrent since the scheme netted the company more than $ 10 million. `` It's just considered a cost of doing business,'' he said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney who prosecuted the case, agreed with <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON>'s reasoning, but said in his letter the <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> antitrust law allows only the imprisonment of executives, not corporations. `` We are not persuaded that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended to authorize courts to imprison corporations,'' <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> wrote. `` Indeed, imprisoning a corporation by having a marshal seize its assets or otherwise limit its operations could adversely affect competition and further injure consumers.'' In response, <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said, `` this Court can not ascribe to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> an intent to incur the costs asociated with effectively enforcing the Sherman Act when violated by individuals but not when violated by corporations.'' When told of <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON>'s opinion, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, defense attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Alleghany </ORGANIZATION>, said he would proceed with his appeal to the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> and use the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> letter to bolster his case. `` I certainly would hope that the letter is beneficial,'' he said. <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Allegheny </PERSON> conspired to set prices from 1982 to 1984. Wholesale prices were inflated 25 percent and the cost was passed on to consumers, according to court records. <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> pleaded guilty to the charge and paid fines of $ 1 million in both <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> Six top officials of the two companies received fines and prison terms. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has said 14 grand juries in 12 states are continuing their investigation of price fixing in the soft drink industry.
