<HEAD>Shippers Say Drought Pulled Plug On Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KOLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Freight companies hauling iron ore, coal and other heavy cargo through the Great Lakes say the summer drought pulled the plug on their shipping season by lowering water levels. But a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> official said Friday the firms should n't blame the hot weather for failing to keep up with heavy demands. The Cleveland-based <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> will ask the corps to give them an extra month to haul cargo through locks at <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. The four locks _ which link <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and the industry-lined <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seaway </LOCATION> _ normally close from Dec. 15 until April 1, when ice clogs the lakes. Shipping giants such as <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steamship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> say evaporation from the drought lowered water levels, forcing ships to lighten their cargoes. They want to use the <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. Marie locks until at least Jan. 15, <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Nekvasil </PERSON> said Friday. The extension would give <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steamship </ORGANIZATION> and the group's 13 other shipping firms time to make extra trips and catch up with an increasing demand for raw materials, <PERSON> Nekvasil </PERSON> said. `` Fleets have been hard pressed to meet current demand,'' he said, adding that increased steel production has boosted 1988 shipments by more than 13 percent. Freight companies may need more time to keep pace with shipments, but they should n't blame the drought for their problems, corps spokesman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Billmaier </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think they hurt much from the drought. I just think they've got more business,'' said <PERSON> Billmaier </PERSON>, chief of operations and maintenance for the corps' <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> district. <PERSON> Billmaier </PERSON> confirmed that water levels have dropped over the past year, but said shipping companies compensated earlier by hauling heavier loads when the water was deeper. `` They ca n't haul loads as big as they could two years ago, that's true,'' he said. `` Maybe they ca n't make as much money. But they can still work the lakes.'' <PERSON> Billmaier </PERSON> said the corps, which controls the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> locks, also restricts winter shipping in an effort to minimize environmental damage. Ships maneuvering through ice jams cause extra water turbulence that kills fish, damages docks and shoreline and disturbs the bottom of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Billmaier </PERSON> said the corps' <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> bureau probably will agree to extend the shipping season by at least two weeks if carriers can prove they need the extra time. He could not predict when a final ruling will be made.
