<HEAD>Third-Quarter Profit In Contrast To Year-Earlier Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 7.1 million in the third quarter in contrast to a loss of $ 70 million in the same period a year earlier. However, results were not as strong as in this year's second quarter, when the company made $ 26.1 million. Revenue in the third quarter was $ 285.5 million, up from $ 261 million a year earlier but down from $ 308 million in this year's second quarter Chairman and Chief Executive Officer W.J. Sanders III blamed the decline from the spring figures on a drop in orders for microprocessors from personal computer manufacturers. He predicted a continued slump. `` We believe that a period of digestion of component inventories on the part of our customers will keep a lid on new orders and hence our sales growth for the next several quarters,'' <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> continued. <ORGANIZATION> AMD </ORGANIZATION> announced it will continue with plans to close its oldest operating silicon wafer factory in December and reduce its workforce in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> by 1,400. The company said it plans to take a charge against fourth-quarter earnings as a result of those plans. <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said he remains `` very positive'' on the longer-term prospects of <ORGANIZATION> AMD </ORGANIZATION>'s future.
