<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs; retransmitting to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have risen in what analysts said was a technical rally inspired by the expiration of November options and efforts to square trading positions before the weekend. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> rose 28 cents Friday to settle at $ 12.94 a barrel. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.63 cent to settle at 40.13 cents a gallon, while home heating oil rose 0.22 cent to 37.46 cents a gallon. Prices moved erratically in a narrow range during the day, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Byers </PERSON> of the oil futures research department at <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. But he said short-covering, in which traders who have sold borrowed contracts buy contracts to square their positions, drove prices higher. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Redoglia </PERSON>, vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>, said there was also some buying connected with the expiration of November options. `` The pressure on the market is still there. Overproduction is still there,'' he said. Earlier in the week, crude oil prices tumbled below $ 13 a barrel to their lowest level in two years as <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the world's largest oil exporter, threatened to produce more than its quota if other members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries continued to pump beyond their quotas The Saudis have indicated they want to punish other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members for overproducing and driving down the price of oil.
